Questions:
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{amssymb}

\begin{document}

\section*{Physics Problem}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] Using the unit vectors $\hat{\imath}$ and $\hat{\jmath}$, write down an expression for the position vector in the polar form.

    \item[(b)] Show that the acceleration is directed towards the centre of the circular motion.
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] In polar coordinates, the position vector $\vec{r}$ can be expressed as:
    \[
    \vec{r} = r \cos\theta \, \hat{\imath} + r \sin\theta \, \hat{\jmath}
    \]
    where $r$ is the radial distance from the origin, $\theta$ is the angle from the positive $x$-axis, $\hat{\imath}$ is the unit vector in the $x$-direction, and $\hat{\jmath}$ is the unit vector in the $y$-direction.

    \item[(b)] For circular motion, the acceleration $\vec{a}$ is given by the centripetal acceleration, which is directed towards the center of the circle. The centripetal acceleration is expressed as:
    \[
    \vec{a} = -\frac{v^2}{r} \, \hat{r}
    \]
    where $v$ is the tangential velocity, $r$ is the radius of the circle, and $\hat{r}$ is the unit vector pointing radially outward. The negative sign indicates that the acceleration is directed towards the center of the circular path, opposite to the radial direction.
\end{enumerate}

\end{document}

