Questions:
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

An object is being weighed on a spring balance going around a curve of radius \( R = 100 \, \text{m} \) at a speed of \( v = 7 \, \text{m/s} \). The object has a weight of \( 50 \, \text{kg wt} \). What reading is registered on the spring balance?

\section*{Solution}

First, we convert the weight of the object from kilograms weight to newtons. The weight given is \( 50 \, \text{kg wt} \), which is equivalent to a mass of \( m = 50 \, \text{kg} \). The gravitational force (weight) is given by:

\[
W = mg = 50 \, \text{kg} \times 9.8 \, \text{m/s}^2 = 490 \, \text{N}
\]

When the object is moving in a circular path, it experiences a centripetal force given by:

\[
F_c = \frac{mv^2}{R}
\]

Substituting the given values:

\[
F_c = \frac{50 \, \text{kg} \times (7 \, \text{m/s})^2}{100 \, \text{m}} = \frac{50 \times 49}{100} = 24.5 \, \text{N}
\]

The reading on the spring balance is the apparent weight, which is the vector sum of the gravitational force and the centripetal force. Since the centripetal force acts horizontally and the gravitational force acts vertically, the apparent weight \( W' \) is given by:

\[
W' = \sqrt{W^2 + F_c^2}
\]

Substituting the values:

\[
W' = \sqrt{(490 \, \text{N})^2 + (24.5 \, \text{N})^2}
\]

\[
W' = \sqrt{240100 + 600.25} = \sqrt{240700.25}
\]

\[
W' \approx 490.6 \, \text{N}
\]

Thus, the reading registered on the spring balance is approximately \( 490.6 \, \text{N} \).

\end{document}

