\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

With what speed must an airplane on the equator fly towards the west so that a passenger in the plane may see the sun as motionless?

\section*{Solution}

To solve this problem, we need to consider the rotational speed of the Earth at the equator. The Earth completes one full rotation (360 degrees) in 24 hours. The circumference of the Earth at the equator can be calculated using the formula:

\[
C = 2 \pi R
\]

where \( R \) is the radius of the Earth. The average radius of the Earth is approximately \SI{6371}{\kilo\meter}. Thus, the circumference is:

\[
C = 2 \pi \times \SI{6371}{\kilo\meter} \approx \SI{40030}{\kilo\meter}
\]

The rotational speed \( v_{\text{earth}} \) of the Earth at the equator is given by:

\[
v_{\text{earth}} = \frac{C}{T}
\]

where \( T = 24 \times 60 \times 60 = 86400 \) seconds is the period of rotation (one day). Substituting the values, we have:

\[
v_{\text{earth}} = \frac{\SI{40030}{\kilo\meter}}{86400 \, \text{seconds}} \approx \SI{463.8}{\meter\per\second}
\]

To make the sun appear motionless to a passenger on the airplane, the airplane must fly westward at the same speed as the Earth's rotational speed at the equator. Therefore, the speed of the airplane \( v_{\text{plane}} \) must be:

\[
v_{\text{plane}} = v_{\text{earth}} \approx \SI{463.8}{\meter\per\second}
\]

Thus, the airplane must fly at approximately \SI{463.8}{\meter\per\second} towards the west.

\end{document}

