\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\title{Moment of Inertia of a Right-Angle Triangular Lamina}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

Consider a right-angle triangular lamina with side lengths of 3 cm, 4 cm, and 5 cm. The moments of inertia of the lamina about these sides are denoted as $I_1$, $I_2$, and $I_3$, respectively (see Fig. 4.1). Show that $I_1 > I_2 > I_3$.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.3\textwidth]{triangle.png} % Replace with actual image file
    \caption{Right-angle triangular lamina with sides 3 cm, 4 cm, and 5 cm.}
    \label{fig:triangle}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

The moment of inertia of a triangular lamina about one of its sides can be calculated using the formula:

\[
I = \frac{1}{3} m a^2
\]

where $m$ is the mass of the lamina and $a$ is the length of the side about which the moment of inertia is being calculated.

For the given triangular lamina:

\begin{align*}
I_1 &= \frac{1}{3} m \times 3^2 = \frac{1}{3} m \times 9 = 3m, \\
I_2 &= \frac{1}{3} m \times 4^2 = \frac{1}{3} m \times 16 = \frac{16}{3}m, \\
I_3 &= \frac{1}{3} m \times 5^2 = \frac{1}{3} m \times 25 = \frac{25}{3}m.
\end{align*}

Since $3m > \frac{16}{3}m > \frac{25}{3}m$, we have:

\[
I_1 > I_2 > I_3
\]

Thus, the moments of inertia satisfy the inequality $I_1 > I_2 > I_3$ as required.

\end{document}

