K_{\text{hollow sphere}} &= \frac{1}{2} \left(\frac{2}{3} m r^2\right) \omega^2 = \frac{1}{3} m r^2 \omega^2 \\
K_{\text{solid disk}} &= \frac{1}{2} \left(\frac{1}{2} m r^2\right) \omega^2 = \frac{1}{4} m r^2 \omega^2 \\
K_{\text{hoop}} &= \frac{1}{2} \left(m r^2\right) \omega^2 = \frac{1}{2} m r^2 \omega^2
\end{align*}

The work done to stop each object is equal to its rotational kinetic energy. Therefore, the object with the maximum rotational kinetic energy will require the maximum work to stop.

Comparing the kinetic energies:
\[
K_{\text{hoop}} > K_{\text{hollow sphere}} > K_{\text{solid disk}} > K_{\text{solid sphere}}
\]

Thus, the hoop requires the maximum work to stop.

\end{document}

