In problem (4.50), the four objects have the same angular momentum. For which object will maximum work have to be done to stop it?

\section*{Solution}

To determine which object requires the maximum work to stop, we need to consider the relationship between work and angular momentum. The work done to stop an object with angular momentum \( L \) is given by the change in its rotational kinetic energy. The rotational kinetic energy \( K \) of an object is given by:

\[
K = \frac{L^2}{2I}
\]

where \( I \) is the moment of inertia of the object. Since all objects have the same angular momentum \( L \), the work done to stop the object is inversely proportional to its moment of inertia \( I \). Therefore, the object with the smallest moment of inertia will require the maximum work to stop.

