\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Physics Problems and Solutions}

\subsection*{(a) Angular Velocity of the Earth}

Given that the Earth rotates once every 23 hours and 56 minutes, we are to calculate the angular velocity, \(\omega\), of the Earth. The Earth rotates counterclockwise (west to east) when viewed from above the North Pole. We also need to determine the direction of \(\omega\).

First, convert the rotation period into seconds:
\[
T = 23 \, \text{hours} + 56 \, \text{minutes} = 23 \times 3600 \, \text{s} + 56 \times 60 \, \text{s} = 86160 \, \text{s}
\]

The angular velocity \(\omega\) is given by:
\[
\omega = \frac{2\pi}{T} = \frac{2\pi}{86160} \, \text{rad/s}
\]

Calculating \(\omega\):
\[
\omega \approx 7.292 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{rad/s}
\]

The direction of \(\omega\) is along the axis of rotation, pointing from the South Pole to the North Pole, which is perpendicular to the plane of rotation.

\subsection*{(b) Foucault's Pendulum Precession}

The Foucault pendulum experiences a precession due to the Coriolis force. The time for one complete rotation of the plane of oscillation at a latitude \(\lambda = 30^\circ\) is given by:

\[
T_{\text{precession}} = \frac{24 \, \text{hours}}{\sin \lambda}
\]

Substituting \(\lambda = 30^\circ\):
\[
T_{\text{precession}} = \frac{24 \, \text{hours}}{\sin 30^\circ} = \frac{24 \, \text{hours}}{0.5} = 48 \, \text{hours}
\]

Thus, the time for one rotation of the plane of oscillation of the Foucault pendulum at \(30^\circ\) latitude is 48 hours.

\end{document}

