\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{physics}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}
An object at the equator is projected upwards with a speed of 20 m/s. How far from its initial position will it land?

\section*{Solution}

To solve this problem, we will assume that the object is projected vertically upwards and that air resistance is negligible. We will also assume that the object lands at the same horizontal position from which it was projected, as there is no horizontal motion involved.

Given:
\begin{align*}
    v_0 &= 20 \, \text{m/s} \quad \text{(initial velocity)} \\
    g &= 9.81 \, \text{m/s}^2 \quad \text{(acceleration due to gravity)}
\end{align*}

The time taken to reach the maximum height is given by:
\[
    t_{\text{up}} = \frac{v_0}{g}
\]

Substituting the given values:
\[
    t_{\text{up}} = \frac{20}{9.81} \approx 2.04 \, \text{s}
\]

The total time of flight is twice the time taken to reach the maximum height (as the time to ascend equals the time to descend):
\[
    t_{\text{total}} = 2 \times t_{\text{up}} = 2 \times 2.04 \approx 4.08 \, \text{s}
\]

The vertical displacement (height) reached by the object can be calculated using the kinematic equation:
\[
    h = v_0 t_{\text{up}} - \frac{1}{2} g t_{\text{up}}^2
\]

Substituting the values:
\[
    h = 20 \times 2.04 - \frac{1}{2} \times 9.81 \times (2.04)^2 \approx 20.4 \, \text{m}
\]

Since the object lands back at the same vertical position from which it was projected, the horizontal displacement (distance from the initial position) is zero.

Thus, the object will land \textbf{0 meters} from its initial position.

\end{document}

