\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A body is thrown vertically upwards with a velocity of \(100 \, \text{m/s}\) at a \(60^\circ\) latitude. Calculate the displacement from the vertical in \(10 \, \text{s}\).

\section*{Solution}

To solve this problem, we need to consider the Coriolis effect due to the Earth's rotation. The Coriolis force can cause a deflection in the path of the object. The displacement from the vertical due to the Coriolis effect is given by:

\[
d = \frac{2 v_0 \omega \sin \phi \cdot t^2}{g}
\]

where:
\begin{align*}
v_0 &= 100 \, \text{m/s} \quad \text{(initial velocity)} \\
\omega &= 7.2921 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{rad/s} \quad \text{(angular velocity of the Earth)} \\
\phi &= 60^\circ \quad \text{(latitude)} \\
t &= 10 \, \text{s} \quad \text{(time)} \\
g &= 9.81 \, \text{m/s}^2 \quad \text{(acceleration due to gravity)}
\end{align*}

Substituting the values into the formula, we have:

\[
d = \frac{2 \times 100 \times 7.2921 \times 10^{-5} \times \sin(60^\circ) \times 10^2}{9.81}
\]

Calculating the above expression:

\[
d \approx \frac{2 \times 100 \times 7.2921 \times 10^{-5} \times 0.866 \times 100}{9.81}
\]

\[
d \approx \frac{126.11}{9.81} \approx 12.86 \, \text{m}
\]

Thus, the displacement from the vertical in 10 seconds is approximately \(12.86 \, \text{m}\).

\end{document}

