\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

\noindent
Considering Fig. 5.1, what is the magnitude of the net gravitational force exerted on the uniform sphere, of mass $0.010 \, \text{kg}$, at point $P$ by the other two uniform spheres, each of mass $0.260 \, \text{kg}$, that are fixed at points $A$ and $B$ as shown? [The University of Wales, Aberystwyth 2005]

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{figure_5_1.png} % Replace with actual figure file
    \caption{Diagram of the spheres at points $A$, $B$, and $P$.}
    \label{fig:5_1}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

To find the magnitude of the net gravitational force on the sphere at point $P$, we use Newton's law of universal gravitation. The gravitational force between two masses $m_1$ and $m_2$ separated by a distance $r$ is given by:

\begin{equation}
    F = \frac{G m_1 m_2}{r^2}
\end{equation}

where $G$ is the gravitational constant, $G = 6.674 \times 10^{-11} \, \text{N m}^2/\text{kg}^2$.

Let $m_P = 0.010 \, \text{kg}$ be the mass at point $P$, and $m_A = m_B = 0.260 \, \text{kg}$ be the masses at points $A$ and $B$. Assume the distances $r_{AP}$ and $r_{BP}$ are known from the figure.

The gravitational force exerted by the mass at $A$ on the mass at $P$ is:

