\begin{document}

\section*{Gravitational Potential Energy of a Uniform Sphere}

We are tasked with showing that the gravitational energy of the Earth, assumed to be a uniform sphere of radius \( R \) and mass \( M \), is given by:

\[
U = -\frac{3}{5} \frac{G M^2}{R}
\]

To find the potential energy of the Earth, assuming it to be a uniform sphere with radius \( R = 6.4 \times 10^6 \, \text{m} \) and mass \( M = 6.0 \times 10^{24} \, \text{kg} \), we can substitute these values into the formula:

\[
U = -\frac{3}{5} \frac{G (6.0 \times 10^{24} \, \text{kg})^2}{6.4 \times 10^6 \, \text{m}}
\]

where \( G = 6.674 \times 10^{-11} \, \text{m}^3 \, \text{kg}^{-1} \, \text{s}^{-2} \) is the gravitational constant.

Calculating this gives:

\[
U = -\frac{3}{5} \times \frac{6.674 \times 10^{-11} \times (6.0 \times 10^{24})^2}{6.4 \times 10^6}
\]

Simplifying further, we find:

\[
U \approx -2.24 \times 10^{32} \, \text{J}
\]

Thus, the gravitational potential energy of the Earth, assuming it to be a uniform sphere, is approximately \(-2.24 \times 10^{32} \, \text{J}\).

\end{document}

