\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A thin wire of linear mass density $\lambda$ is bent in the form of a quarter circle of radius $R$ (see Fig. 5.2). Calculate the gravitational intensity at the center $O$.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.3\textwidth]{quarter_circle.png} % Replace with the actual figure file
    \caption{Quarter circle wire configuration}
    \label{fig:quarter_circle}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

To find the gravitational intensity at the center $O$, we consider the wire as a quarter circle with radius $R$. The linear mass density of the wire is $\lambda$, so the mass element $dm$ can be expressed as:

\[
dm = \lambda \, R \, d\theta
\]

where $d\theta$ is the differential angle subtended by the mass element at the center $O$.

The gravitational field $d\mathbf{g}$ due to the mass element $dm$ at the center $O$ is given by:

\[
d\mathbf{g} = \frac{G \, dm}{R^2} = \frac{G \, \lambda \, R \, d\theta}{R^2} = \frac{G \, \lambda \, d\theta}{R}
\]

The direction of $d\mathbf{g}$ is radially inward towards the center $O$. Due to symmetry, the horizontal components of the gravitational field from opposite sides of the wire cancel out, leaving only the vertical components to sum up.

The vertical component of $d\mathbf{g}$ is:

\[
d\mathbf{g}_y = d\mathbf{g} \sin\theta = \frac{G \, \lambda \, d\theta}{R} \sin\theta
\]

To find the total gravitational intensity $\mathbf{g}$ at $O$, integrate $d\mathbf{g}_y$ from $\theta = 0$ to $\theta = \frac{\pi}{2}$:

\[
\mathbf{g} = \int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \frac{G \, \lambda}{R} \sin\theta \, d\theta
\]

This integral evaluates to:

\[
\mathbf{g} = \frac{G \, \lambda}{R} \left[ -\cos\theta \right]_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}} = \frac{G \, \lambda}{R} \left( 0 + 1 \right) = \frac{G \, \lambda}{R}
\]

Thus, the gravitational intensity at the center $O$ is:

\[
\mathbf{g} = \frac{G \, \lambda}{R}
\]

\end{document}

