\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem: Gravitational Field of a Spherical Shell}

The cross-section of a spherical shell of uniform density and mass $M$ and of radii $a$ and $b$ is shown in Fig. 5.4. How does the gravitational field vary in the region $a < r < b$?

\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{figure5_4.png} % Replace with actual figure file
    \captionof{figure}{Cross-section of a spherical shell}
\end{center}

\section*{Solution}

To determine the gravitational field in the region $a < r < b$, we consider the properties of a spherical shell. According to the shell theorem, the gravitational field inside a spherical shell of uniform density is zero. Therefore, for a point located at a distance $r$ such that $a < r < b$, the gravitational field is given by:

\[
\mathbf{g}(r) = 0 \quad \text{for} \quad a < r < b
\]

This result follows from the fact that the gravitational forces exerted by the shell's mass elements cancel each other out at any point inside the shell.

\end{document}

