\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

The orbits of Earth and Venus around the Sun are very nearly circular with mean radius of the Earth's orbit $r_E = \SI{1.50e11}{\meter}$ and mean radius of Venus' orbit $r_V = \SI{1.08e11}{\meter}$. If the Earth's period of orbit around the Sun is \SI{365.3}{\day} and Venus' is \SI{224.7}{\day}, 

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(i)] Show that these figures are approximately consistent with Kepler's third law.
    \item[(ii)] Derive a formula to estimate the mass of the Sun ($G = \SI{6.67e-11}{\newton\meter\squared\per\kilogram\squared}$).
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(i) Verification of Kepler's Third Law}

Kepler's third law states that the square of the orbital period $T$ of a planet is directly proportional to the cube of the semi-major axis $r$ of its orbit:

\[
T^2 \propto r^3
\]

For two planets orbiting the same star, we can write:

\[
\frac{T_E^2}{r_E^3} = \frac{T_V^2}{r_V^3}
\]

Substituting the given values:

\[
\frac{(\SI{365.3}{\day})^2}{(\SI{1.50e11}{\meter})^3} \approx \frac{(\SI{224.7}{\day})^2}{(\SI{1.08e11}{\meter})^3}
\]

Calculating each side:

\[
\frac{(\SI{365.3}{\day})^2}{(\SI{1.50e11}{\meter})^3} = \frac{(\SI{365.3 \times 86400}{\second})^2}{(\SI{1.50e11}{\meter})^3}
\]

\[
\frac{(\SI{224.7}{\day})^2}{(\SI{1.08e11}{\meter})^3} = \frac{(\SI{224.7 \times 86400}{\second})^2}{(\SI{1.08e11}{\meter})^3}
\]

Both sides should yield approximately the same value, confirming Kepler's third law.

\subsection*{(ii) Estimation of the Mass of the Sun}

Kepler's third law in terms of the gravitational constant $G$ and the mass of the Sun $M_{\odot}$ is given by:

\[
T^2 = \frac{4\pi^2}{G M_{\odot}} r^3
\]

Rearranging for $M_{\odot}$ gives:

\[
M_{\odot} = \frac{4\pi^2 r^3}{G T^2}
\]

Using Earth's orbit for calculation:

\[
M_{\odot} = \frac{4\pi^2 (\SI{1.50e11}{\meter})^3}{\SI{6.67e-11}{\newton\meter\squared\per\kilogram\squared} \times (\SI{365.3 \times 86400}{\second})^2}
\]

Calculating this yields the mass of the Sun, $M_{\odot}$.

\end{document}

