\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A 4 kg mass at the end of a spring moves with Simple Harmonic Motion (SHM) on a horizontal frictionless table with period 2 s and amplitude 2 m. Determine:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The spring constant, \( k \).
    \item The maximum force exerted on the spring.
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Spring Constant}

The period \( T \) of a mass-spring system in SHM is given by the formula:
\[
T = 2\pi \sqrt{\frac{m}{k}}
\]
where \( m = 4 \, \text{kg} \) is the mass and \( k \) is the spring constant. Rearranging the formula to solve for \( k \), we have:
\[
k = \frac{4\pi^2 m}{T^2}
\]

Substituting the given values \( T = 2 \, \text{s} \) and \( m = 4 \, \text{kg} \):
\[
k = \frac{4\pi^2 \times 4}{2^2} = \frac{16\pi^2}{4} = 4\pi^2 \, \text{N/m}
\]

\subsection*{(b) Maximum Force Exerted on the Spring}

The maximum force exerted on the spring, \( F_{\text{max}} \), occurs at the maximum displacement (amplitude) and is given by Hooke's Law:
\[
F_{\text{max}} = k \cdot A
\]
where \( A = 2 \, \text{m} \) is the amplitude.

Using the spring constant calculated in part (a):
\[
F_{\text{max}} = 4\pi^2 \times 2 = 8\pi^2 \, \text{N}
\]

Thus, the maximum force exerted on the spring is \( 8\pi^2 \, \text{N} \).

\end{document}

