\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A 2 kg weight is placed on a vertical spring, stretching it 5 cm. The weight is pulled down a distance of 10 cm and released. Find (a) the spring constant; (b) the amplitude; (c) the frequency of oscillations.

\section*{Solution}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] \textbf{Spring Constant, \( k \):}

    The spring constant \( k \) can be found using Hooke's Law:
    \[
    F = kx
    \]
    where \( F \) is the force applied and \( x \) is the displacement. The force \( F \) is equal to the weight of the object:
    \[
    F = mg = 2 \, \text{kg} \times 9.8 \, \text{m/s}^2 = 19.6 \, \text{N}
    \]
    The displacement \( x \) is 5 cm or 0.05 m. Thus, the spring constant \( k \) is:
    \[
    k = \frac{F}{x} = \frac{19.6 \, \text{N}}{0.05 \, \text{m}} = 392 \, \text{N/m}
    \]

    \item[(b)] \textbf{Amplitude, \( A \):}

    The amplitude \( A \) is the maximum displacement from the equilibrium position. Since the weight is pulled down an additional 10 cm, the amplitude is:
    \[
    A = 10 \, \text{cm} = 0.1 \, \text{m}
    \]

    \item[(c)] \textbf{Frequency of Oscillations, \( f \):}

    The frequency of oscillations can be found using the formula:
    \[
    f = \frac{1}{T} = \frac{1}{2\pi} \sqrt{\frac{k}{m}}
    \]
    Substituting the known values:
    \[
    f = \frac{1}{2\pi} \sqrt{\frac{392 \, \text{N/m}}{2 \, \text{kg}}} = \frac{1}{2\pi} \sqrt{196} = \frac{1}{2\pi} \times 14
    \]
    \[
    f \approx \frac{14}{6.28} \approx 2.23 \, \text{Hz}
    \]

\end{enumerate}

\end{document}

