\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A U-tube is filled with a liquid, the total length of the liquid column being $h$. If the liquid on one side is slightly depressed by blowing gently down, the levels of the liquid will oscillate about the equilibrium position before finally coming to rest.

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] Show that the oscillations are Simple Harmonic Motion (SHM).
    \item[(b)] Find the period of oscillations.
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] To show that the oscillations are SHM, consider the forces acting on the liquid column. When the liquid is displaced by a small distance $x$ from its equilibrium position, the restoring force $F$ is proportional to the displacement $x$, i.e., $F = -kx$, where $k$ is a constant. This is the defining characteristic of SHM.

    \item[(b)] The period $T$ of the oscillations can be determined using the formula for the period of a simple harmonic oscillator:
    \[
    T = 2\pi \sqrt{\frac{m}{k}}
    \]
    where $m$ is the effective mass of the oscillating liquid column and $k$ is the spring constant equivalent for the liquid. To find $m$ and $k$, consider the geometry and properties of the U-tube and the liquid.
\end{enumerate}

\end{document}

