\title{Physics Problem: Effective Spring Constant}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

A mass $m$ is connected to two springs with spring constants $k_1$ and $k_2$ in parallel, as shown in Fig. 6.13. Calculate the effective (equivalent) spring constant.

\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{Fig6_13.png} % Replace with the actual path to the figure file
    \captionof{figure}{Two springs in parallel connected to a mass $m$.}
\end{center}

\section*{Solution}

When two springs are connected in parallel, the effective spring constant $k_{\text{eff}}$ is the sum of the individual spring constants. Therefore, the effective spring constant is given by:

\begin{equation}
    k_{\text{eff}} = k_1 + k_2
\end{equation}

This is because the force exerted by the springs in parallel is the sum of the forces exerted by each spring, and the displacement is the same for both springs.

