\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\title{Physics Problem: Oscillation of a Mass on a Frictionless Table}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

A mass $m$ is placed on a frictionless horizontal table and is connected to fixed points $A$ and $B$ by two springs of negligible mass and of equal natural length with spring constants $k_1$ and $k_2$, as shown in Fig. 6.14. The mass is displaced along the $x$-axis and released. Calculate the period of oscillation.

\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{fig6_14.png} % Placeholder for Fig. 6.14
\end{center}

\section*{Solution}

When the mass is displaced by a small distance $x$ along the $x$-axis, the restoring force due to the springs is given by Hooke's law:

\[
F = -k_1 x - k_2 x = -(k_1 + k_2)x
\]

This force leads to simple harmonic motion, where the equation of motion is:

\[
m \frac{d^2 x}{dt^2} = -(k_1 + k_2)x
\]

This can be rewritten as:

\[
\frac{d^2 x}{dt^2} + \frac{k_1 + k_2}{m} x = 0
\]

The angular frequency $\omega$ of the oscillation is given by:

\[
\omega = \sqrt{\frac{k_1 + k_2}{m}}
\]

The period of oscillation $T$ is related to the angular frequency by:

\[
T = \frac{2\pi}{\omega} = 2\pi \sqrt{\frac{m}{k_1 + k_2}}
\]

Thus, the period of oscillation is:

\[
T = 2\pi \sqrt{\frac{m}{k_1 + k_2}}
\]

\end{document}

