\section*{Problem 6.46: Normal Coordinates}

In this problem, we express the equations of motion and the energy in terms of normal coordinates. 

\subsection*{Equations of Motion}

The equations of motion in terms of normal coordinates \( q_i \) can be written as:
\begin{equation}
    \ddot{q}_i + \omega_i^2 q_i = 0,
\end{equation}
where \( \omega_i \) are the normal mode frequencies.

\subsection*{Energy in Normal Coordinates}

The energy of the system in terms of normal coordinates is given by:
\begin{equation}
    E = \frac{1}{2} \sum_i \left( \dot{q}_i^2 + \omega_i^2 q_i^2 \right).
\end{equation}

\subsection*{Characteristics of Normal Coordinates}

Normal coordinates have the following characteristics:
\begin{itemize}
    \item They decouple the equations of motion, allowing each normal coordinate to oscillate independently.
    \item Each normal coordinate corresponds to a normal mode of the system, characterized by a specific frequency \( \omega_i \).
    \item The transformation to normal coordinates is typically achieved through a linear transformation that diagonalizes the system's mass and stiffness matrices.
\end{itemize}

\end{document}

