\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

The equation of a transverse wave traveling on a rope is given by:

\[
y = 5 \sin \left( \pi (0.02x - 4.00t) \right),
\]

where \( y \) and \( x \) are expressed in centimetres and \( t \) is in seconds. Find the amplitude, frequency, velocity, and wavelength of the wave.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Amplitude:} The amplitude of the wave is the coefficient of the sine function, which is \( 5 \) cm.

    \item \textbf{Angular Frequency and Wave Number:} The wave equation is of the form \( y = A \sin(kx - \omega t) \), where \( A \) is the amplitude, \( k \) is the wave number, and \( \omega \) is the angular frequency. Comparing with the given equation, we have:
    \[
    k = \pi \times 0.02 = 0.02\pi \quad \text{cm}^{-1}
    \]
    \[
    \omega = \pi \times 4.00 = 4.00\pi \quad \text{s}^{-1}
    \]

    \item \textbf{Frequency:} The frequency \( f \) is given by:
    \[
    f = \frac{\omega}{2\pi} = \frac{4.00\pi}{2\pi} = 2.00 \quad \text{Hz}
    \]

    \item \textbf{Wavelength:} The wavelength \( \lambda \) is related to the wave number \( k \) by:
    \[
    \lambda = \frac{2\pi}{k} = \frac{2\pi}{0.02\pi} = 100 \quad \text{cm}
    \]

    \item \textbf{Velocity:} The velocity \( v \) of the wave is given by:
    \[
    v = \frac{\omega}{k} = \frac{4.00\pi}{0.02\pi} = 200 \quad \text{cm/s}
    \]
\end{itemize}

\end{document}

