\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\title{Physics Problem: Resultant Amplitude of Combined Waves}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

Two sinusoidal waves having the same frequency and traveling in the same direction are combined. If their amplitudes are \(6.0 \, \text{cm}\) and \(8.0 \, \text{cm}\) and have a phase difference of \(\frac{\pi}{2}\), determine the amplitude of the resultant motion.

\section*{Solution}

The amplitude of the resultant wave when two waves interfere can be determined using the formula:

\[
A = \sqrt{A_1^2 + A_2^2 + 2A_1A_2\cos\phi}
\]

where \(A_1 = 6.0 \, \text{cm}\), \(A_2 = 8.0 \, \text{cm}\), and \(\phi = \frac{\pi}{2}\).

Substituting the given values:

\[
A = \sqrt{(6.0)^2 + (8.0)^2 + 2 \times 6.0 \times 8.0 \times \cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)}
\]

Since \(\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right) = 0\), the equation simplifies to:

\[
A = \sqrt{(6.0)^2 + (8.0)^2}
\]

\[
A = \sqrt{36 + 64}
\]

\[
A = \sqrt{100}
\]

\[
A = 10.0 \, \text{cm}
\]

Thus, the amplitude of the resultant motion is \(10.0 \, \text{cm}\).

\end{document}

