Questions:
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

The speed of a wave on a string is given by the equation:
\[
v = \sqrt{\frac{F}{\mu}}
\]
where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( v \) is the speed of the wave,
    \item \( F \) is the tension in the string (units: Newtons, \( \text{N} \)),
    \item \( \mu \) is the linear mass density of the string (units: kilograms per meter, \( \text{kg/m} \)).
\end{itemize}

To show that the right-hand side of this equation has the units of speed, we analyze the units:

\[
\sqrt{\frac{F}{\mu}} = \sqrt{\frac{\text{N}}{\text{kg/m}}}
\]

Recall that 1 Newton is equivalent to 1 kg m/s\(^2\). Therefore, the units become:

\[
\sqrt{\frac{\text{kg m/s}^2}{\text{kg/m}}} = \sqrt{\frac{\text{m}^2}{\text{s}^2}} = \frac{\text{m}}{\text{s}}
\]

Thus, the units of the right-hand side simplify to meters per second, which are indeed the units of speed.

\end{document}

