\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

(a) A steel bar of density \( \rho = 7860 \, \text{kg/m}^3 \) and Youngs modulus \( E = 2 \times 10^{11} \, \text{N/m}^2 \) and of length \( L = 0.25 \, \text{m} \) is rigidly clamped at one end and free to move at the other end. Determine the fundamental frequency of the bar for longitudinal harmonic vibrations.

(b) How do the frequencies compare with 
\begin{itemize}
    \item (i) rod free at both ends;
    \item (ii) bar clamped at the midpoint;
    \item (iii) bar clamped at both ends.
\end{itemize}

\section*{Solution}

(a) The fundamental frequency \( f \) of a bar clamped at one end and free at the other end for longitudinal vibrations is given by:

\[
f = \frac{1}{4L} \sqrt{\frac{E}{\rho}}
\]

Substituting the given values:

\[
f = \frac{1}{4 \times 0.25} \sqrt{\frac{2 \times 10^{11}}{7860}}
\]

Calculating the expression:

\[
f = \frac{1}{1} \sqrt{\frac{2 \times 10^{11}}{7860}}
\]

\[
f = \sqrt{\frac{2 \times 10^{11}}{7860}} \approx 318.5 \, \text{Hz}
\]

(b) Comparison of frequencies:

\begin{itemize}
    \item (i) For a rod free at both ends, the fundamental frequency is given by:

    \[
    f_{\text{free}} = \frac{1}{2L} \sqrt{\frac{E}{\rho}}
    \]

    \item (ii) For a bar clamped at the midpoint, it behaves like two bars each of length \( L/2 \) clamped at one end and free at the other, so the fundamental frequency is:

    \[
    f_{\text{midpoint}} = \frac{1}{4(L/2)} \sqrt{\frac{E}{\rho}} = \frac{1}{2L} \sqrt{\frac{E}{\rho}}
    \]

    \item (iii) For a bar clamped at both ends, the fundamental frequency is:

    \[
    f_{\text{clamped}} = \frac{1}{2L} \sqrt{\frac{E}{\rho}}
    \]
\end{itemize}

Thus, the frequency for the bar clamped at one end and free at the other is lower than the frequencies for the other configurations.

\end{document}

