Questions:
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

The dispersion relation for water waves of very short wavelength in deep water is given by:

\begin{equation}
    \omega^2 = \frac{S}{\rho}k^3,
\end{equation}

where \( S \) is the surface tension and \( \rho \) is the density.

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] \textbf{Phase Velocity:}

    The phase velocity \( v_p \) is defined as:

    \begin{equation}
        v_p = \frac{\omega}{k}.
    \end{equation}

    Substituting the dispersion relation, we have:

    \begin{equation}
        v_p = \frac{\sqrt{\frac{S}{\rho}k^3}}{k} = \sqrt{\frac{S}{\rho}k}.
    \end{equation}

    \item[(b)] \textbf{Group Velocity:}

    The group velocity \( v_g \) is defined as:

    \begin{equation}
        v_g = \frac{d\omega}{dk}.
    \end{equation}

    Differentiating the dispersion relation with respect to \( k \), we get:

    \begin{equation}
        \omega = \sqrt{\frac{S}{\rho}k^3},
    \end{equation}

    \begin{equation}
        \frac{d\omega}{dk} = \frac{1}{2} \left( \frac{S}{\rho} \right)^{1/2} \cdot 3k^{1/2} = \frac{3}{2} \sqrt{\frac{S}{\rho}k}.
    \end{equation}

    Thus, the group velocity is:

    \begin{equation}
        v_g = \frac{3}{2} \sqrt{\frac{S}{\rho}k}.
    \end{equation}

    \item[(c)] \textbf{Comparison of Group and Phase Velocities:}

    Comparing the expressions for the phase and group velocities, we have:

    \begin{equation}
        v_g = \frac{3}{2} v_p.
    \end{equation}

    Therefore, the group velocity is greater than the phase velocity.
\end{enumerate}

\end{document}

