\begin{document}

For water, the density \( \rho = 10^3 \, \text{kg/m}^3 \) and the surface tension \( S = 0.075 \, \text{N/m} \). We need to calculate the phase velocity \( v_p \) and the group velocity \( v_g \) in deep water for small ripples with wavelength \( \lambda = 1 \, \text{cm} \) and for large waves with \( \lambda = 1 \, \text{m} \).

\section*{Solution}

The phase velocity \( v_p \) for deep water waves is given by the formula:
\[
v_p = \sqrt{\frac{g \lambda}{2\pi} + \frac{2\pi S}{\rho \lambda}}
\]

The group velocity \( v_g \) is related to the phase velocity by:
\[
v_g = \frac{d(\omega)}{d(k)}
\]
where \( \omega \) is the angular frequency and \( k \) is the wave number, \( k = \frac{2\pi}{\lambda} \).

For small ripples with \( \lambda = 1 \, \text{cm} = 0.01 \, \text{m} \):
\[
v_p = \sqrt{\frac{g \times 0.01}{2\pi} + \frac{2\pi \times 0.075}{1000 \times 0.01}}
\]

For large waves with \( \lambda = 1 \, \text{m} \):
\[
v_p = \sqrt{\frac{g \times 1}{2\pi} + \frac{2\pi \times 0.075}{1000 \times 1}}
\]

Here, \( g \) is the acceleration due to gravity, approximately \( 9.81 \, \text{m/s}^2 \).

\end{document}

