The dispersion relation for sound waves in air is given by:

\begin{equation}
\omega = \sqrt{\frac{\gamma R T}{M}} \, k
\end{equation}

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\omega$ is the angular frequency,
    \item $\gamma$ is the adiabatic index,
    \item $R$ is the universal gas constant,
    \item $T$ is the absolute temperature,
    \item $M$ is the molar mass of the gas,
    \item $k$ is the wave number.
\end{itemize}

To find the phase velocity $v_p$ and the group velocity $v_g$, we use the following definitions:

\begin{equation}
v_p = \frac{\omega}{k} = \sqrt{\frac{\gamma R T}{M}}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
v_g = \frac{d\omega}{dk} = \sqrt{\frac{\gamma R T}{M}}
\end{equation}

Since the dispersion relation is linear, the phase velocity and the group velocity are equal in this case.

\end{document}

