\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Harmonic Variation of Displacement and Pressure in a Plane Wave}

Let the displacement \( s(x, t) \) and pressure \( p(x, t) \) of a plane wave vary harmonically. We can express them as:

\begin{align}
    s(x, t) &= s_0 \cos(kx - \omega t + \phi_s), \\
    p(x, t) &= p_0 \cos(kx - \omega t + \phi_p),
\end{align}

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( s_0 \) is the displacement amplitude,
    \item \( p_0 \) is the pressure amplitude,
    \item \( k \) is the wave number,
    \item \( \omega \) is the angular frequency,
    \item \( \phi_s \) and \( \phi_p \) are the phase constants for displacement and pressure, respectively.
\end{itemize}

The pressure \( p(x, t) \) in a plane wave is related to the displacement \( s(x, t) \) by the equation of motion and the adiabatic relation between pressure and density. For a plane wave traveling in a medium, the pressure is given by:

\begin{equation}
    p(x, t) = -B \frac{\partial s(x, t)}{\partial x},
\end{equation}

where \( B \) is the bulk modulus of the medium.

Substituting the expression for \( s(x, t) \) into the pressure equation, we have:

\begin{align}
    p(x, t) &= -B \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \left[ s_0 \cos(kx - \omega t + \phi_s) \right] \\
    &= -B \left[ -s_0 k \sin(kx - \omega t + \phi_s) \right] \\
    &= B s_0 k \sin(kx - \omega t + \phi_s).
\end{align}

Recognizing that \( \sin(\theta) = \cos(\theta - \frac{\pi}{2}) \), we can rewrite the pressure as:

\begin{equation}
    p(x, t) = B s_0 k \cos(kx - \omega t + \phi_s - \frac{\pi}{2}).
\end{equation}

Comparing with the expression for \( p(x, t) \), we see:

\begin{equation}
    \phi_p = \phi_s - \frac{\pi}{2}.
\end{equation}

This shows that the displacement is 90 out of phase with the pressure wave.

Finally, equating the amplitudes from the harmonic expressions, we have:

\begin{equation}
    p_0 = B s_0 k.
\end{equation}

Thus, the relationship between the pressure amplitude and the displacement amplitude is given by:

\begin{equation}
    s_0 = \frac{p_0}{B k}.
\end{equation}

\end{document}

