\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

Assuming $\rho = 1.29 \, \text{kg/m}^3$ for the density of air and $v = 331 \, \text{m/s}$ for the speed of sound, find the pressure amplitude corresponding to the threshold of hearing intensity of $10^{-12} \, \text{W/m}^2$.

\section*{Solution}

The intensity $I$ of a sound wave is related to the pressure amplitude $p_0$ by the equation:

\[
I = \frac{p_0^2}{2 \rho v}
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $I = 10^{-12} \, \text{W/m}^2$ is the intensity at the threshold of hearing,
    \item $\rho = 1.29 \, \text{kg/m}^3$ is the density of air,
    \item $v = 331 \, \text{m/s}$ is the speed of sound.
\end{itemize}

Rearranging the formula to solve for the pressure amplitude $p_0$, we have:

\[
p_0 = \sqrt{2 \rho v I}
\]

Substituting the given values:

\[
p_0 = \sqrt{2 \times 1.29 \, \text{kg/m}^3 \times 331 \, \text{m/s} \times 10^{-12} \, \text{W/m}^2}
\]

Calculating the above expression:

\[
p_0 = \sqrt{2 \times 1.29 \times 331 \times 10^{-12}}
\]

\[
p_0 \approx \sqrt{8.538 \times 10^{-10}}
\]

\[
p_0 \approx 2.92 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{Pa}
\]

Thus, the pressure amplitude corresponding to the threshold of hearing intensity is approximately $2.92 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{Pa}$.

\end{document}

