\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

Two trains move away from each other at a speed of 25 m/s relative to the earth's surface. One gives a 520 Hz signal. Find the frequency heard by the observer on the other train (sound velocity = 330 m/s).

\section*{Solution}

To find the frequency heard by the observer on the other train, we use the Doppler effect formula for sound:

\[
f' = f \frac{v + v_o}{v + v_s}
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( f' \) is the observed frequency,
    \item \( f = 520 \, \text{Hz} \) is the source frequency,
    \item \( v = 330 \, \text{m/s} \) is the speed of sound in air,
    \item \( v_o = 25 \, \text{m/s} \) is the speed of the observer (the second train),
    \item \( v_s = 25 \, \text{m/s} \) is the speed of the source (the first train).
\end{itemize}

Since the trains are moving away from each other, the observer perceives a lower frequency. Thus, the formula becomes:

\[
f' = 520 \, \text{Hz} \times \frac{330 \, \text{m/s} + 25 \, \text{m/s}}{330 \, \text{m/s} + 25 \, \text{m/s}}
\]

Simplifying the expression:

\[
f' = 520 \, \text{Hz} \times \frac{330 + 25}{330 + 25} = 520 \, \text{Hz} \times \frac{355}{355}
\]

\[
f' = 520 \, \text{Hz} \times 1 = 520 \, \text{Hz}
\]

Therefore, the frequency heard by the observer on the other train is \( f' = 520 \, \text{Hz} \).

\end{document}

