\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A whistle of frequency \( f_0 = 540 \, \text{Hz} \) rotates in a circle of radius \( r = 2 \, \text{m} \) at an angular speed of \( \omega = 15.0 \, \text{rad/s} \). What are the maximum and minimum frequencies heard by a listener, standing at a long distance away at rest from the center of the circle? Assume the speed of sound is \( v = 330 \, \text{m/s} \).

\section*{Solution}

The frequency heard by the listener is affected by the Doppler effect. The maximum and minimum frequencies occur when the velocity of the whistle is directly towards or away from the listener.

The linear speed \( v_s \) of the whistle is given by:
\[
v_s = \omega \cdot r = 15.0 \, \text{rad/s} \times 2 \, \text{m} = 30 \, \text{m/s}
\]

Using the Doppler effect formula, the observed frequency \( f \) is:
\[
f = f_0 \frac{v}{v \mp v_s}
\]

- For the maximum frequency (\( f_{\text{max}} \)), the whistle moves towards the listener:
  \[
  f_{\text{max}} = f_0 \frac{v}{v - v_s} = 540 \, \text{Hz} \times \frac{330 \, \text{m/s}}{330 \, \text{m/s} - 30 \, \text{m/s}}
  \]
  \[
  f_{\text{max}} = 540 \, \text{Hz} \times \frac{330}{300} = 594 \, \text{Hz}
  \]

- For the minimum frequency (\( f_{\text{min}} \)), the whistle moves away from the listener:
  \[
  f_{\text{min}} = f_0 \frac{v}{v + v_s} = 540 \, \text{Hz} \times \frac{330 \, \text{m/s}}{330 \, \text{m/s} + 30 \, \text{m/s}}
  \]
  \[
  f_{\text{min}} = 540 \, \text{Hz} \times \frac{330}{360} = 495 \, \text{Hz}
  \]

Thus, the maximum frequency heard by the listener is \( 594 \, \text{Hz} \) and the minimum frequency is \( 495 \, \text{Hz} \).

\end{document}

