\section*{Kundt's Tube Experiment}

In the Kundts tube experiment, the length of the steel rod which is stroked is 120 cm long, and the distance between heaps of cork dust is 8 cm when the rod is caused to vibrate longitudinally in air. If the ends of the tube are sealed and the air is replaced by a gas, and the experiment is repeated, the distance between heaps is observed to be 10 cm.

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] \textbf{Velocity of sound in the gas:}

    Let \( v_{\text{air}} = 340 \, \text{m/s} \) be the velocity of sound in air. The wavelength of sound in air is given by the distance between two consecutive heaps of cork dust, which is 8 cm or 0.08 m.

    The frequency of the sound in air is:
    \[
    f = \frac{v_{\text{air}}}{\lambda_{\text{air}}} = \frac{340}{0.08} \, \text{Hz}
    \]

    When the air is replaced by the gas, the distance between heaps is 10 cm or 0.10 m. Assuming the frequency remains the same, the velocity of sound in the gas \( v_{\text{gas}} \) is given by:
    \[
    v_{\text{gas}} = f \times \lambda_{\text{gas}} = \frac{340}{0.08} \times 0.10
    \]
    \[
    v_{\text{gas}} = 425 \, \text{m/s}
    \]

    \item[(b)] \textbf{Velocity of sound in the rod:}

    The rod is 120 cm or 1.2 m long, and it vibrates in its fundamental mode. In this mode, the rod has two nodes at the ends and an antinode in the middle, making the rod length half of the wavelength of the sound in the rod.

    Therefore, the wavelength in the rod \( \lambda_{\text{rod}} \) is:
    \[
    \lambda_{\text{rod}} = 2 \times 1.2 = 2.4 \, \text{m}
    \]

    The frequency of the sound in the rod is the same as in air, so:
    \[
    f = \frac{340}{0.08} \, \text{Hz}
    \]

    The velocity of sound in the rod \( v_{\text{rod}} \) is:
    \[
    v_{\text{rod}} = f \times \lambda_{\text{rod}} = \frac{340}{0.08} \times 2.4
    \]
    \[
    v_{\text{rod}} = 10200 \, \text{m/s}
    \]

\end{enumerate}

\end{document}

