\begin{document}

\title{Resonance in a Closed Tube}
\author{University of London}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

Air in a tube closed at one end vibrates in resonance with a tuning fork whose frequencies are 210 and 350 vibrations per second, when the temperature is \SI{20}{\degreeCelsius}. Explain how this is possible and find the effective length of the tube. Assume that the velocity of sound in air at \SI{0}{\degreeCelsius} is \SI{331.5}{\centi\meter\per\second}.

\section*{Solution}

The velocity of sound in air at a temperature \( T \) in degrees Celsius can be given by the formula:
\[
v = v_0 \sqrt{1 + \frac{T}{273}}
\]
where \( v_0 = \SI{331.5}{\centi\meter\per\second} \) is the velocity of sound at \SI{0}{\degreeCelsius}.

Substituting \( T = \SI{20}{\degreeCelsius} \):
\[
v = \SI{331.5}{\centi\meter\per\second} \times \sqrt{1 + \frac{20}{273}}
\]

Calculating the above expression:
\[
v \approx \SI{331.5}{\centi\meter\per\second} \times \sqrt{1.0733} \approx \SI{343}{\centi\meter\per\second}
\]

For a tube closed at one end, the resonant frequencies \( f_n \) are given by:
\[
f_n = \frac{(2n-1)v}{4L}
\]
where \( n \) is the harmonic number, \( v \) is the velocity of sound, and \( L \) is the effective length of the tube.

Given the resonant frequencies \( f_1 = \SI{210}{\hertz} \) and \( f_2 = \SI{350}{\hertz} \), we can write:
\[
f_1 = \frac{v}{4L} \quad \text{and} \quad f_2 = \frac{3v}{4L}
\]

Solving for \( L \) using \( f_1 \):
\[
L = \frac{v}{4f_1} = \frac{\SI{343}{\centi\meter\per\second}}{4 \times \SI{210}{\hertz}}
\]
\[
L \approx \frac{\SI{343}{\centi\meter\per\second}}{\SI{840}{\hertz}} \approx \SI{0.408}{\meter}
\]

Thus, the effective length of the tube is approximately \SI{0.408}{\meter}.

\end{document}

