\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\title{Physics Problem: Rate of Flow in a Gas Pipeline}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

An apparatus is mounted along the axis of a gas pipeline of cross-sectional area \( A \). Calculate the rate of flow of the gas across the section of the pipe if \( h \) is the difference in the liquid column and \( \rho_L \) and \( \rho_g \) are the densities of the liquid and the gas, respectively. Refer to Fig. 9.3.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{figure9_3.png} % Replace with actual figure file
    \caption{Schematic of the gas pipeline with apparatus mounted.}
    \label{fig:9_3}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

The rate of flow of the gas can be determined using the Bernoulli's equation and the principle of conservation of mass. The pressure difference due to the height difference \( h \) in the liquid column is given by:

\[
\Delta P = \rho_L g h
\]

where \( \rho_L \) is the density of the liquid and \( g \) is the acceleration due to gravity.

Assuming the flow is steady and incompressible, the rate of flow \( Q \) can be expressed as:

\[
Q = A v
\]

where \( v \) is the velocity of the gas. From Bernoulli's equation, the velocity \( v \) can be related to the pressure difference as:

\[
v = \sqrt{\frac{2 \Delta P}{\rho_g}}
\]

Substituting the expression for \( \Delta P \), we have:

\[
v = \sqrt{\frac{2 \rho_L g h}{\rho_g}}
\]

Thus, the rate of flow \( Q \) is:

\[
Q = A \sqrt{\frac{2 \rho_L g h}{\rho_g}}
\]

This equation provides the rate of flow of the gas across the section of the pipe.

\end{document}

