\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Mean Free Path}

The \textbf{mean free path} is defined as the average distance a molecule travels between collisions in a gas. Mathematically, it can be expressed as:

\begin{equation}
    \lambda = \frac{v}{Z}
\end{equation}

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\lambda$ is the mean free path,
    \item $v$ is the mean molecular velocity,
    \item $Z$ is the collision frequency (number of collisions per second).
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Calculation}

Given:
\begin{align*}
    Z &= 2 \times 10^{10} \, \text{s}^{-1}, \\
    v &= 1000 \, \text{m/s}.
\end{align*}

Substituting these values into the formula for the mean free path:

\begin{equation}
    \lambda = \frac{1000 \, \text{m/s}}{2 \times 10^{10} \, \text{s}^{-1}}
\end{equation}

Calculating the above expression:

\begin{align*}
    \lambda &= \frac{1000}{2 \times 10^{10}} \\
    &= 5 \times 10^{-8} \, \text{m}.
\end{align*}

Thus, the mean free path of a molecule in the gas is \(5 \times 10^{-8}\) meters.

\end{document}

