\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{amssymb}

\begin{document}

The MaxwellBoltzmann distribution of speeds is given by:

\begin{equation}
f(v) = 4\pi \left( \frac{m}{2\pi k T} \right)^{3/2} v^2 e^{-\frac{mv^2}{2kT}}
\end{equation}

To find the most probable speed, \( v_{\text{mp}} \), we need to maximize the function \( f(v) \) with respect to \( v \). This involves taking the derivative of \( f(v) \) with respect to \( v \) and setting it to zero:

\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dv} \left[ 4\pi \left( \frac{m}{2\pi k T} \right)^{3/2} v^2 e^{-\frac{mv^2}{2kT}} \right] = 0
\end{equation}

Simplifying the derivative, we find:

\begin{equation}
\left( \frac{d}{dv} \left[ v^2 \right] \right) e^{-\frac{mv^2}{2kT}} + v^2 \left( \frac{d}{dv} \left[ e^{-\frac{mv^2}{2kT}} \right] \right) = 0
\end{equation}

This results in:

\begin{equation}
2v e^{-\frac{mv^2}{2kT}} - \frac{mv^3}{kT} e^{-\frac{mv^2}{2kT}} = 0
\end{equation}

Factoring out common terms:

\begin{equation}
v e^{-\frac{mv^2}{2kT}} \left( 2 - \frac{mv^2}{kT} \right) = 0
\end{equation}

For non-zero \( v \), we have:

\begin{equation}
2 - \frac{mv^2}{kT} = 0
\end{equation}

Solving for \( v \), we find the most probable speed:

\begin{equation}
v_{\text{mp}} = \sqrt{\frac{2kT}{m}}
\end{equation}

Thus, the most probable speed is given by:

\[
v_{\text{mp}} = \left( \frac{2kT}{m} \right)^{1/2}
\]

\end{document}

