Van der Waal's equation can be written in terms of moles per volume as:

\[
n V = \left( \frac{p + \frac{a n^2}{V^2}}{RT} \right) \left( 1 - \frac{b n}{V} \right)
\]

The van der Waal's parameters for hydrogen sulphide gas (H\(_2\)S) are \(a = 0.448 \, \text{J m}^3/\text{mol}^2\) and \(b = 4.29 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{m}^3/\text{mol}\). Determine an estimate of the number of moles per volume of H\(_2\)S gas at \(127^\circ \text{C}\) and a pressure of \(9.80 \times 10^5 \, \text{Pa}\) as follows:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] Calculate as a first approximation using the ideal gas equation, \(n V = \frac{p}{RT}\).
    \item[(b)] Substitute this first approximation into the right-hand side of the equation derived in part (a) to find a new approximation of \(n V\) (on the left-hand side) that takes into account real gas effects.
\end{enumerate}

\end{document}

