\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\title{Heat Transfer Problem}
\author{University of Dublin}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

A block of ice is kept pressed against one end of a circular copper bar of diameter \SI{2}{\centi\meter}, length \SI{20}{\centi\meter}, and thermal conductivity \SI{90}{\watt\per\meter\per\kelvin}. The other end is kept at \SI{100}{\degreeCelsius} by means of a steam chamber. How long will it take to melt \SI{50}{\gram} of ice, assuming heat is only supplied to the ice along the bar? The latent heat of fusion of ice is \( L = 8 \times 10^4 \, \si{\calorie\per\kilogram} \).

\section*{Solution}

First, convert the latent heat of fusion from calories to joules:
\[
L = 8 \times 10^4 \, \si{\calorie\per\kilogram} \times 4.184 \, \si{\joule\per\calorie} = 3.3472 \times 10^5 \, \si{\joule\per\kilogram}
\]

The mass of ice is:
\[
m = \SI{50}{\gram} = 0.05 \, \si{\kilogram}
\]

The heat required to melt the ice is:
\[
Q = m \cdot L = 0.05 \, \si{\kilogram} \times 3.3472 \times 10^5 \, \si{\joule\per\kilogram} = 16736 \, \si{\joule}
\]

The cross-sectional area \( A \) of the copper bar is:
\[
A = \pi \left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^2 = \pi \left(\frac{0.02}{2}\right)^2 = \pi \times 0.01^2 = \pi \times 10^{-4} \, \si{\meter\squared}
\]

Using Fourier's law of heat conduction, the rate of heat transfer \( \dot{Q} \) is given by:
\[
\dot{Q} = \frac{k \cdot A \cdot \Delta T}{L}
\]
where
\begin{align*}
k &= \SI{90}{\watt\per\meter\per\kelvin}, \\
\Delta T &= \SI{100}{\degreeCelsius} - \SI{0}{\degreeCelsius} = \SI{100}{\kelvin}, \\
L &= \SI{0.2}{\meter}.
\end{align*}

Substituting the values, we get:
\[
\dot{Q} = \frac{90 \times \pi \times 10^{-4} \times 100}{0.2} = 141.37 \, \si{\watt}
\]

The time \( t \) required to transfer the heat \( Q \) is:
\[
t = \frac{Q}{\dot{Q}} = \frac{16736}{141.37} \approx 118.4 \, \si{\second}
\]

Thus, it will take approximately \SI{118.4}{\second} to melt \SI{50}{\gram} of ice.

\end{document}

