\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A mass of ice forms on the surface that is \SI{1}{\centi\meter} thick. If the air temperature is \SI{-10}{\degreeCelsius}, find the rate (in \si{\meter\per\hour}) at which ice is added to the bottom of the layer. The density of ice is \SI{917}{\kilo\gram\per\meter\cubed}, the thermal conductivity of ice is \SI{0.59}{\watt\per\meter\per\kelvin}, and the latent heat of fusion is \SI{333}{\kilo\joule\per\kilo\gram}. Assume that the underlying water is at \SI{0}{\degreeCelsius}.

\section*{Solution}

To find the rate at which ice is added to the bottom of the layer, we can use the heat conduction equation and the relation between heat transfer and phase change.

The heat transfer through the ice layer is given by Fourier's law:

\begin{equation}
    Q = k \cdot A \cdot \frac{\Delta T}{d}
\end{equation}

where:
\begin{align*}
    Q & \text{ is the heat transfer rate (W)}, \\
    k & = \SI{0.59}{\watt\per\meter\per\kelvin} \text{ is the thermal conductivity of ice}, \\
    A & \text{ is the area (m\(^2\))}, \\
    \Delta T & = \SI{10}{\kelvin} \text{ is the temperature difference}, \\
    d & = \SI{0.01}{\meter} \text{ is the thickness of the ice layer}.
\end{align*}

The rate of ice formation is related to the heat transfer by the latent heat of fusion:

\begin{equation}
    Q = m \cdot L
\end{equation}

where:
\begin{align*}
    m & \text{ is the mass of ice formed (kg)}, \\
    L & = \SI{333}{\kilo\joule\per\kilo\gram} = \SI{333000}{\joule\per\kilo\gram} \text{ is the latent heat of fusion}.
\end{align*}

The mass of ice formed per unit time is:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{dm}{dt} = \frac{Q}{L}
\end{equation}

The volume of ice formed per unit time is:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{dV}{dt} = \frac{dm}{dt} \cdot \frac{1}{\rho}
\end{equation}

where \(\rho = \SI{917}{\kilo\gram\per\meter\cubed}\) is the density of ice.

Substituting the expressions for \(Q\) and \(\frac{dm}{dt}\), we have:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{dV}{dt} = \frac{k \cdot A \cdot \Delta T}{d \cdot L \cdot \rho}
\end{equation}

Finally, the rate at which ice is added to the bottom of the layer (in \si{\meter\per\hour}) is:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{dh}{dt} = \frac{dV}{dt} \cdot \frac{1}{A} = \frac{k \cdot \Delta T}{d \cdot L \cdot \rho}
\end{equation}

Substitute the given values:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{dh}{dt} = \frac{0.59 \cdot 10}{0.01 \cdot 333000 \cdot 917} \approx \SI{0.000019}{\meter\per\second}
\end{equation}

Convert \(\frac{dh}{dt}\) to \si{\meter\per\hour}:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{dh}{dt} \approx \SI{0.000019}{\meter\per\second} \times \SI{3600}{\second\per\hour} \approx \SI{0.0684}{\meter\per\hour}

