\title{Heat Required for Temperature Increase with Phase Transition}
\author{University of Manchester 2007}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

The latent heat of fusion of a material is 6 kJ/mol, and the heat capacity (\( C_p \)) in solid and liquid phases of the material is a linear function of temperature: 
\[
C_p = 30.6 + 0.0103T \quad \text{(J/mol/K)}
\]
How much heat is required to increase the temperature of 1 mol of the material from 20C to 200C if the fusion phase transition occurs at 80C?

\section*{Solution}

The total heat required, \( Q \), is the sum of the heat required to:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Heat the solid from 20C to 80C.
    \item Perform the phase transition at 80C.
    \item Heat the liquid from 80C to 200C.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection*{1. Heating the Solid from 20C to 80C}

The heat required to increase the temperature of the solid from 20C to 80C is given by:
\[
Q_1 = \int_{20}^{80} C_p \, dT = \int_{20}^{80} (30.6 + 0.0103T) \, dT
\]

Calculating the integral:
\[
Q_1 = \left[ 30.6T + 0.0103 \frac{T^2}{2} \right]_{20}^{80}
\]

\[
Q_1 = \left( 30.6 \times 80 + 0.0103 \times \frac{80^2}{2} \right) - \left( 30.6 \times 20 + 0.0103 \times \frac{20^2}{2} \right)
\]

\[
Q_1 = (2448 + 32.96) - (612 + 2.06) = 2468.9 \, \text{J}
\]

\subsection*{2. Phase Transition at 80C}

The heat required for the phase transition is the latent heat of fusion:
\[
Q_2 = 6 \, \text{kJ/mol} = 6000 \, \text{J/mol}
\]

\subsection*{3. Heating the Liquid from 80C to 200C}

The heat required to increase the temperature of the liquid from 80C to 200C is given by:
\[
Q_3 = \int_{80}^{200} C_p \, dT = \int_{80}^{200} (30.6 + 0.0103T) \, dT
\]

Calculating the integral:
\[
Q_3 = \left[ 30.6T + 0.0103 \frac{T^2}{2} \right]_{80}^{200}
\]

\[
Q_3 = \left( 30.6 \times 200 + 0.0103 \times \frac{200^2}{2} \right) - \left( 30.6 \times 80 + 0.0103 \times \frac{80^2}{2} \right)
\]

\[
Q_3 = (6120 + 206) - (2448 + 32.96) = 3845.04 \, \text{J}
\]

\subsection*{Total Heat Required}

The total heat required is the sum of \( Q_1 \), \( Q_2 \), and \( Q_3 \):
\[
Q = Q_1 + Q_2 + Q_3 = 2468.9 + 6000 + 3845.04 = 12313.94 \, \text{J}
\]

Thus, the total heat required is approximately \(

