    \item[(ii)] \textbf{Isochoric Process:} An isochoric process is a thermodynamic process in which the volume remains constant. Since the volume does not change, no work is done by or on the system, and any heat added or removed results in a change in the internal energy and temperature.

    \item[(iii)] \textbf{Adiabatic Process:} An adiabatic process is a thermodynamic process in which no heat is exchanged with the surroundings. In this process, the system is perfectly insulated, and changes in internal energy are due solely to work done on or by the system.

    \item[(iv)] \textbf{Isothermal Process:} An isothermal process is a thermodynamic process in which the temperature remains constant. During this process, the system can exchange heat with its surroundings, and any work done is compensated by heat exchange to maintain constant temperature.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection*{(b) Work Done in Adiabatic Compression}

The work done on a gas during an adiabatic compression from initial conditions \((P_1, V_1)\) to final conditions \((P_2, V_2)\) is given by the equation:

\begin{equation}
    W = \frac{1}{\gamma - 1} (P_2 V_2 - P_1 V_1)
\end{equation}

where \(\gamma\) is the adiabatic index, also known as the heat capacity ratio, defined as \(\gamma = \frac{C_p}{C_v}\), with \(C_p\) being the heat capacity at constant pressure and \(C_v\) the heat capacity at constant volume.

