\begin{document}

\section*{Adiabatic Process for a Monatomic Ideal Gas}

To show that for a monatomic ideal gas undergoing an adiabatic process, \( PV^{5/3} = \text{constant} \), we start with the first law of thermodynamics:

\begin{equation}
    dU = \delta Q - \delta W
\end{equation}

For an adiabatic process, there is no heat exchange, so \(\delta Q = 0\). Thus, the first law simplifies to:

\begin{equation}
    dU = -\delta W
\end{equation}

For an ideal gas, the work done \(\delta W\) is given by:

\begin{equation}
    \delta W = PdV
\end{equation}

Substituting into the first law, we have:

\begin{equation}
    dU = -PdV
\end{equation}

The internal energy \(U\) of a monatomic ideal gas is given by:

\begin{equation}
    U = \frac{3}{2}nRT
\end{equation}

Differentiating, we find:

\begin{equation}
    dU = \frac{3}{2}nR \, dT
\end{equation}

Equating the expressions for \(dU\):

\begin{equation}
    \frac{3}{2}nR \, dT = -PdV
\end{equation}

Using the ideal gas law \(PV = nRT\), we can express \(P\) as:

\begin{equation}
    P = \frac{nRT}{V}
\end{equation}

Substituting for \(P\) in the equation for \(dU\), we get:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{3}{2}nR \, dT = -\frac{nRT}{V} \, dV
\end{equation}

Dividing through by \(nR\) and rearranging gives:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{3}{2} \frac{dT}{T} = -\frac{dV}{V}
\end{equation}

Integrating both sides:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{3}{2} \ln T = -\ln V + C
\end{equation}

Exponentiating both sides, we obtain:

\begin{equation}
    T^{3/2} V = e^C
\end{equation}

Using the ideal gas law again, \(T = \frac{PV}{nR}\), we substitute for \(T\):

\begin{equation}
    \left(\frac{PV}{nR}\right)^{3/2} V = \text{constant}
\end{equation}

Simplifying:

\begin{equation}
    P^{3/2} V^{5/2} = \text{constant}
\end{equation}

Rearranging gives:

\begin{equation}
    PV^{5/3} = \text{constant}
\end{equation}

Thus, for a monatomic ideal gas undergoing an adiabatic process, \( PV^{5/3} = \text{constant} \).

