    \end{enumerate}
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) First Law of Thermodynamics}

The first law of thermodynamics in its infinitesimal form is given by:
\[
dU = \delta Q - \delta W
\]
where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $dU$ is the infinitesimal change in internal energy of the system. It is a state function and hence path independent.
    \item $\delta Q$ is the infinitesimal heat added to the system. It is path dependent.
    \item $\delta W$ is the infinitesimal work done by the system. It is also path dependent.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{(b) Work Done During Isothermal Compression}

For an isothermal process, the temperature $T$ remains constant. The work done on the gas during an isothermal compression from volume $V_1$ to $V_2$ is given by:
\[
