\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\title{Physics Problem: Heat Engine Efficiency}
\author{Osmania University 2004}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

A heat engine absorbs heat of \SI{105}{\kilo\calorie} from a source, which is at \SI{127}{\degreeCelsius}, and rejects a part of the heat to a sink at \SI{27}{\degreeCelsius}. Calculate the efficiency of the engine and the work done by it.

\section*{Solution}

First, we convert the temperatures from Celsius to Kelvin:
\begin{align*}
    T_1 &= 127 + 273.15 = \SI{400.15}{\kelvin}, \\
    T_2 &= 27 + 273.15 = \SI{300.15}{\kelvin}.
\end{align*}

The efficiency \(\eta\) of a Carnot engine is given by:
\[
\eta = 1 - \frac{T_2}{T_1}
\]

Substituting the values:
\begin{align*}
    \eta &= 1 - \frac{300.15}{400.15} \\
         &= 1 - 0.75 \\
         &= 0.25.
\end{align*}

Thus, the efficiency of the engine is \(25\%\).

Next, we calculate the work done by the engine. The work done \(W\) is given by:
\[
W = Q_1 \times \eta
\]

where \(Q_1 = \SI{105}{\kilo\calorie}\). Converting \(\SI{105}{\kilo\calorie}\) to joules:
\[
Q_1 = 105 \times 4184 = \SI{439320}{\joule}
\]

Now, calculate the work done:
\begin{align*}
    W &= 439320 \times 0.25 \\
      &= \SI{109830}{\joule}.
\end{align*}

Therefore, the work done by the engine is \(\SI{109830}{\joule}\).

\end{document}

