\begin{document}

\section*{Problem Statement}

(a) \(1 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{m}^3\) of He at normal conditions (\(p_0 = 1 \, \text{bar}\), \(T_0 = 0^\circ\text{C}\)) is heated to a final temperature of \(500 \, \text{K}\). What is the entropy change for 
\begin{itemize}
    \item[(i)] an isobaric process and 
    \item[(ii)] an isochoric process? 
\end{itemize}
Use \(C_P^{\text{He}} = 21 \, \text{J/(mol K)}\) and \(C_V^{\text{He}} = 12.7 \, \text{J/(mol K)}\).

(b) Calculate the change in entropy \(\Delta S_1\) for \(1 \, \text{kg}\) of water being heated from \(0\) to \(50^\circ\text{C}\). Compare this change in entropy \(\Delta S_2\) for \(0.5 \, \text{kg}\) of water at \(0^\circ\text{C}\) being mixed with \(0.5 \, \text{kg}\) of water at a temperature of \(100^\circ\text{C}\). Use \(C_V^{\text{H}_2\text{O}} = 4.13 \times 10^3 \, \text{J/(kg K)}\).

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Entropy Change for Helium}

\subsubsection*{(i) Isobaric Process}

The entropy change for an isobaric process is given by:
\[
\Delta S = n C_P \ln \left(\frac{T_f}{T_i}\right)
\]
where \(n\) is the number of moles, \(C_P\) is the molar heat capacity at constant pressure, \(T_i\) is the initial temperature, and \(T_f\) is the final temperature.

\subsubsection*{(ii) Isochoric Process}

The entropy change for an isochoric process is given by:
\[
\Delta S = n C_V \ln \left(\frac{T_f}{T_i}\right)
\]
where \(C_V\) is the molar heat capacity at constant volume.

\subsection*{(b) Entropy Change for Water}

\subsubsection*{Heating 1 kg of Water from \(0^\circ\text{C}\) to \(50^\circ\text{C}\)}

The entropy change is given by:
\[
\Delta S_1 = m C_V \ln \left(\frac{T_f}{T_i}\right)
\]
where \(m\) is the mass of the water, \(C_V\) is the specific heat capacity at constant volume, \(T_i = 273.15 \, \text{K}\), and \(T_f = 323.15 \, \text{K}\).

\subsubsection*{Mixing 0.5 kg of Water at \(0^\circ\text{C}\) with 0.5 kg at \(100^\circ\text{C}\)}

The final temperature \(T_f\) after mixing can be calculated using the principle of conservation of energy. The entropy change \(\Delta S_2\) is then calculated using:
\[
\Delta S_2 = m_1 C_V \ln \left(\frac{T_f}{T_{i1}}\right) + m_2 C_V \ln \left(\frac{T_f}{T_{i2}}\right)
\]
where \(m_1 = m_2 = 0.5 \, \text{kg}\), \(T_{i1} = 273.15 \, \text{K}\), and \(T_{i2} = 373.15 \, \text{K}\).

\end{document}

