\section*{Physics Problems and Solutions}

\subsection*{(a) Shear Modulus Calculation}

A force is applied to the surface of a material with a surface area of $1 \, \text{m}^2$ that exerts a shear across the material (see Fig. 10.4). The sample has a thickness of $10 \, \text{cm}$ and causes the surface to be displaced by $0.1 \, \text{cm}$. What is the shear modulus of the material?

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{shear_deformation.png}
    \caption{Shear deformation}
    \label{fig:shear_deformation}
\end{figure}

The shear modulus \( G \) is defined as:

\[
G = \frac{F/A}{\Delta x / L}
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( F \) is the force applied,
    \item \( A = 1 \, \text{m}^2 \) is the area,
    \item \( \Delta x = 0.1 \, \text{cm} = 0.001 \, \text{m} \) is the displacement,
    \item \( L = 10 \, \text{cm} = 0.1 \, \text{m} \) is the thickness.
\end{itemize}

Substitute the values into the formula to find \( G \).

\subsection*{(b) Bulk Modulus Calculation}

What is the bulk modulus of a material if a $100 \, \text{MPa}$ increase in pressure causes a $1\%$ reduction in its volume?

The bulk modulus \( K \) is defined as:

\[
K = -\frac{\Delta P}{\Delta V / V}
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( \Delta P = 100 \, \text{MPa} = 100 \times 10^6 \, \text{Pa} \),
    \item \( \Delta V / V = 0.01 \) (since it is a $1\%$ reduction).
\end{itemize}

Substitute the values into the formula to find \( K \).

\end{document}

