\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

To solve the problem of determining the height to which a liquid will rise in a capillary tube, we can use the formula for capillary rise:

\[
h = \frac{2 \gamma \cos \theta}{\rho g r}
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( h \) is the height the liquid rises,
    \item \( \gamma \) is the surface tension of the liquid (in N/m),
    \item \( \theta \) is the contact angle (assumed to be \(0^\circ\) for complete wetting, so \(\cos \theta = 1\)),
    \item \( \rho \) is the density of the liquid (in kg/m\(^3\)),
    \item \( g \) is the acceleration due to gravity (approximately \(9.81 \, \text{m/s}^2\)),
    \item \( r \) is the radius of the capillary tube (in meters).
\end{itemize}

Given:
\begin{align*}
    \gamma &= 0.072 \, \text{N/m}, \\
    \rho &= 1000 \, \text{kg/m}^3 \quad (\text{since } 1 \, \text{kg/L} = 1000 \, \text{kg/m}^3), \\
    r &= 1 \, \text{mm} = 0.001 \, \text{m}.
\end{align*}

Substituting these values into the formula, we have:

\[
h = \frac{2 \times 0.072 \times 1}{1000 \times 9.81 \times 0.001}
\]

Calculating the above expression:

\[
h = \frac{0.144}{9.81} \approx 0.0147 \, \text{m} = 14.7 \, \text{mm}
\]

Thus, the liquid will rise approximately \(14.7 \, \text{mm}\) up the capillary.

\end{document}

