\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A small hollow vessel which has a small hole in it is immersed in water to a depth of 45 cm before any water penetrates into the vessel. If the surface tension of water is 0.073 N/m, what should be the radius of the hole?

\section*{Solution}

To solve this problem, we will use the concept of surface tension and the pressure difference across the surface of the water due to the depth.

The pressure difference due to the depth $h$ in a liquid of density $\rho$ is given by:
\[
\Delta P = \rho g h
\]
where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\rho$ is the density of water ($\approx 1000 \, \text{kg/m}^3$),
    \item $g$ is the acceleration due to gravity ($\approx 9.81 \, \text{m/s}^2$),
    \item $h$ is the depth of immersion ($0.45 \, \text{m}$).
\end{itemize}

The pressure difference due to surface tension $\gamma$ for a hole of radius $r$ is given by:
\[
\Delta P = \frac{2\gamma}{r}
\]

Equating the two expressions for pressure difference, we have:
\[
\rho g h = \frac{2\gamma}{r}
\]

Solving for $r$, we get:
\[
r = \frac{2\gamma}{\rho g h}
\]

Substituting the given values:
\begin{align*}
\gamma &= 0.073 \, \text{N/m}, \\
\rho &= 1000 \, \text{kg/m}^3, \\
g &= 9.81 \, \text{m/s}^2, \\
h &= 0.45 \, \text{m},
\end{align*}

we find:
\[
r = \frac{2 \times 0.073}{1000 \times 9.81 \times 0.45}
\]

Calculating the above expression:
\[
r \approx \frac{0.146}{4414.5} \approx 3.31 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{m}
\]

Thus, the radius of the hole should be approximately \(3.31 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{m}\).

\end{document}

