\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

What will be the depth of water at which an air bubble of radius \( r = 0.3 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{m} \) may remain in equilibrium? Given that the surface tension of water is \( \gamma = 0.072 \, \text{N/m} \) and the acceleration due to gravity is \( g = 9.8 \, \text{m/s}^2 \).

\section*{Solution}

The pressure difference across the surface of the bubble due to surface tension is given by the Young-Laplace equation:

\[
\Delta P = \frac{2\gamma}{r}
\]

where:
\begin{align*}
\gamma &= 0.072 \, \text{N/m}, \\
r &= 0.3 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{m}.
\end{align*}

Substitute the given values:

\[
\Delta P = \frac{2 \times 0.072}{0.3 \times 10^{-3}} = \frac{0.144}{0.3 \times 10^{-3}} = 480 \, \text{Pa}
\]

The pressure difference due to the depth \( h \) of water is given by:

\[
\Delta P = \rho g h
\]

where \( \rho \) is the density of water, approximately \( 1000 \, \text{kg/m}^3 \).

Equating the two expressions for \(\Delta P\):

\[
480 = 1000 \times 9.8 \times h
\]

Solving for \( h \):

\[
h = \frac{480}{1000 \times 9.8} = \frac{480}{9800} \approx 0.049 \, \text{m}
\]

Thus, the depth of water at which the air bubble may remain in equilibrium is approximately \( 0.049 \, \text{m} \).

\end{document}

