\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\title{Electric Field at the Center of a Square}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

Charges are placed at the four corners of a square of side $a$, as shown in Fig. 11.3. Find the magnitude and direction of the electric field at the center of the square.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth]{figure11_3.png} % Replace with actual image file
    \caption{Charges at the corners of a square}
    \label{fig:11_3}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

To find the electric field at the center of the square, we consider the contributions from each charge. Let the charges be $q_1, q_2, q_3, q_4$ located at the corners of the square. The distance from each charge to the center of the square is $\frac{a}{\sqrt{2}}$.

The electric field due to a point charge $q$ at a distance $r$ is given by:
\[
\mathbf{E} = \frac{k \cdot q}{r^2} \hat{\mathbf{r}}
\]
where $k = \frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_0}$ is Coulomb's constant and $\hat{\mathbf{r}}$ is the unit vector pointing from the charge to the point of interest.

Since the square is symmetric, the horizontal and vertical components of the electric fields due to opposite charges will cancel each other out if the charges are equal and opposite. Therefore, we need to calculate the resultant electric field vector at the center.

Assuming all charges are equal, the net electric field $\mathbf{E}_{\text{net}}$ at the center is:
\[
\mathbf{E}_{\text{net}} = 4 \cdot \frac{k \cdot q}{\left(\frac{a}{\sqrt{2}}\right)^2} \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \hat{\mathbf{r}}
\]

Simplifying, we get:
\[
\mathbf{E}_{\text{net}} = \frac{4kq}{a^2} \hat{\mathbf{r}}
\]

The direction of the electric field will depend on the configuration of the charges. If all charges are the same, the electric field will point outward from the center. If opposite charges are equal, the field will point towards the positive charge.

\end{document}

