\begin{document}

\title{Physics Problem: Interaction Energy of Charges}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

Three charges \( +q \), \( +q \), and \( Q \) are located at the vertices of a right-angled isosceles triangle, as shown in Fig. 11.6. If the total interaction energy is zero, what should be the value of \( Q \)?

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth]{triangle.png} % Replace with the actual path to the figure
    \caption{Charges at the vertices of a right-angled isosceles triangle.}
    \label{fig:triangle}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

The interaction energy \( U \) of the system of charges can be expressed as the sum of the pairwise potential energies:

\begin{equation}
U = k_e \left( \frac{q \cdot q}{r} + \frac{q \cdot Q}{r} + \frac{q \cdot Q}{r} \right),
\end{equation}

where \( k_e \) is Coulomb's constant and \( r \) is the distance between the charges \( +q \) and \( Q \).

Given that the total interaction energy is zero, we have:

\begin{equation}
k_e \left( \frac{q^2}{r} + \frac{2qQ}{r} \right) = 0.
\end{equation}

Simplifying, we find:

\begin{equation}
q^2 + 2qQ = 0.
\end{equation}

Solving for \( Q \), we get:

\begin{equation}
Q = -\frac{q}{2}.
\end{equation}

Thus, the value of \( Q \) should be \( -\frac{q}{2} \) for the total interaction energy to be zero.

\end{document}

