\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

Figure 11.8 shows the linear quadrupole. Show that the electric potential $V(r)$ at a distance $r \gg d$ from the central charge and in a direction normal to the axis of the quadrupole varies inversely as the third power of $r$.

\section*{Solution}

The electric potential $V(r)$ due to a linear quadrupole at a point $P$ located at a distance $r$ from the central charge and in a direction normal to the axis of the quadrupole can be expressed as:

\begin{equation}
V(r) = \frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_0} \left( \frac{qd}{r^3} \right)
\end{equation}

where $q$ is the magnitude of the charge, $d$ is the separation between the charges, and $\varepsilon_0$ is the permittivity of free space.

For $r \gg d$, the potential $V(r)$ simplifies to:

\begin{equation}
V(r) \approx \frac{K}{r^3}
\end{equation}

where $K$ is a constant that depends on the specific configuration of the quadrupole.

Thus, the electric potential $V(r)$ varies inversely as the third power of $r$, confirming the given statement.

\end{document}

