Questions:
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{amssymb}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

Consider an isolated non-conducting sheet with charge density $\sigma$. The electric field at 25 cm from the sheet is found to be 200 V/m, directed towards the sheet. Calculate $\sigma$ on the sheet. What electric field is expected at 2 cm from its surface? How are the values of $\sigma$ and $E$ changed if a conducting sheet is substituted?

\section*{Solution}

For an infinite non-conducting sheet with surface charge density $\sigma$, the electric field $E$ at a distance from the sheet is given by:

\[
E = \frac{\sigma}{2\varepsilon_0}
\]

Given that the electric field $E = 200 \, \text{V/m}$ at a distance of 25 cm from the sheet, we can calculate $\sigma$ as follows:

\[
\sigma = 2\varepsilon_0 E
\]

Substituting the given values:

\[
\sigma = 2 \times (8.85 \times 10^{-12} \, \text{C}^2/\text{N}\cdot\text{m}^2) \times 200 \, \text{V/m} = 3.54 \times 10^{-9} \, \text{C/m}^2
\]

Next, we calculate the electric field at 2 cm from the surface of the non-conducting sheet. Since the electric field due to an infinite sheet is uniform and does not depend on the distance from the sheet, the electric field remains:

\[
E = 200 \, \text{V/m}
\]

If a conducting sheet is substituted, the electric field outside the conducting sheet is zero because the charges redistribute themselves on the surface to cancel any internal electric field. Therefore, the electric field $E$ outside the conducting sheet is:

\[
E = 0 \, \text{V/m}
\]

The surface charge density $\sigma$ on a conducting sheet would still be the same as calculated above, but the field outside the conductor would be zero.

\end{document}

