\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A coil of wire has a resistance of \SI{20}{\ohm} at \SI{25}{\degreeCelsius} and \SI{25.7}{\ohm} at \SI{100}{\degreeCelsius}. Calculate the temperature coefficient. [University of London]

\section*{Solution}

The temperature coefficient of resistance, \(\alpha\), can be calculated using the formula:

\[
\alpha = \frac{R_2 - R_1}{R_1 \times (T_2 - T_1)}
\]

where:
\begin{align*}
R_1 &= \SI{20}{\ohm} \quad \text{(resistance at } T_1 = \SI{25}{\degreeCelsius}\text{)} \\
R_2 &= \SI{25.7}{\ohm} \quad \text{(resistance at } T_2 = \SI{100}{\degreeCelsius}\text{)} \\
T_1 &= \SI{25}{\degreeCelsius} \\
T_2 &= \SI{100}{\degreeCelsius}
\end{align*}

Substituting the given values into the formula:

\[
\alpha = \frac{\SI{25.7}{\ohm} - \SI{20}{\ohm}}{\SI{20}{\ohm} \times (\SI{100}{\degreeCelsius} - \SI{25}{\degreeCelsius})}
\]

\[
\alpha = \frac{\SI{5.7}{\ohm}}{\SI{20}{\ohm} \times \SI{75}{\degreeCelsius}}
\]

\[
\alpha = \frac{\SI{5.7}{\ohm}}{\SI{1500}{\ohm \degreeCelsius}}
\]

\[
\alpha = \SI{0.0038}{\per\degreeCelsius}
\]

Thus, the temperature coefficient of resistance is \(\alpha = \SI{0.0038}{\per\degreeCelsius}\).

\end{document}

