\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A \SI{60}{\watt} - \SI{100}{\volt} tungsten lamp has a resistance of \SI{20}{\ohm} at air temperature (\SI{0}{\degreeCelsius}). What is the rise in temperature of the filament under normal working conditions? The temperature coefficient of resistance of tungsten is \SI{0.0052}{\per\degreeCelsius}. \textit{[University of London]}

\section*{Solution}

To find the rise in temperature of the filament, we use the formula for the resistance of a material as a function of temperature:

\begin{equation}
    R = R_0 (1 + \alpha \Delta T)
\end{equation}

where:
\begin{align*}
    R & = \text{resistance at the working temperature} \\
    R_0 & = \text{resistance at \SI{0}{\degreeCelsius}} = \SI{20}{\ohm} \\
    \alpha & = \text{temperature coefficient of resistance} = \SI{0.0052}{\per\degreeCelsius} \\
    \Delta T & = \text{rise in temperature}
\end{align*}

The power \( P \) is given by

\begin{equation}
    P = \frac{V^2}{R}
\end{equation}

where \( P = \SI{60}{\watt} \) and \( V = \SI{100}{\volt} \).

Rearranging for \( R \), we have:

\begin{equation}
    R = \frac{V^2}{P} = \frac{(100)^2}{60} = \SI{166.67}{\ohm}
\end{equation}

Substituting \( R \) and \( R_0 \) into the resistance-temperature equation:

\begin{equation}
    166.67 = 20 (1 + 0.0052 \Delta T)
\end{equation}

Solving for \( \Delta T \):

\begin{align*}
    166.67 &= 20 + 20 \times 0.0052 \Delta T \\
    166.67 - 20 &= 20 \times 0.0052 \Delta T \\
    146.67 &= 0.104 \Delta T \\
    \Delta T &= \frac{146.67}{0.104} \approx \SI{1410.29}{\degreeCelsius}
\end{align*}

Thus, the rise in temperature of the filament under normal working conditions is approximately \SI{1410.29}{\degreeCelsius}.

\end{document}

