\section*{Problem Statement}

Two bulbs, \(A_2\) with a power rating of 5 W and \(B_1\) with a power rating of 100 W, are connected in series and joined to the mains (see Fig. \ref{fig:bulbs}). Which bulb will glow brighter? \\
\textit{[Indian Institute of Technology 1979]}

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    % Replace 'example-image' with the actual image file name
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{example-image}
    \caption{Circuit diagram of bulbs connected in series.}
    \label{fig:bulbs}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

When two bulbs are connected in series, the same current flows through both bulbs. The brightness of a bulb is determined by the power it dissipates, which is given by \(P = I^2 R\), where \(I\) is the current and \(R\) is the resistance of the bulb.

Given:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Bulb \(A_2\): 5 W
    \item Bulb \(B_1\): 100 W
\end{itemize}

Assuming both bulbs are rated for the same voltage, the resistance \(R\) of each bulb can be calculated using the formula \(P = \frac{V^2}{R}\), where \(V\) is the voltage rating of the bulb.

The bulb with the higher resistance will dissipate more power when connected in series, as the current is constant. Therefore, the bulb with the lower power rating (5 W) will have a higher resistance and will glow brighter.

Thus, bulb \(A_2\) will glow brighter than bulb \(B_1\).

\end{document}

