\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

Twelve cells having the same emf are connected in series and are kept in a closed box. Some of the cells are wrongly connected. This battery is connected in series with an ammeter and two cells identical with others. The current is 3 A when the cells and the battery aid each other and is 2 A when the cells and the battery oppose each other. How many cells in the battery are wrongly connected? [Indian Institute of Technology 1976]

\section*{Solution}

Let the emf of each cell be \( E \) and the internal resistance of each cell be \( r \).

\begin{itemize}
    \item Let \( n \) be the number of cells wrongly connected.
    \item The effective emf when all cells aid each other is \( (12 - 2n)E + 2E \).
    \item The effective emf when the cells and the battery oppose each other is \( (12 - 2n)E - 2E \).
\end{itemize}

The total internal resistance of the battery is \( 14r \) (since there are 12 cells in the battery and 2 external cells).

Using Ohm's Law \( V = IR \), we have:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{(12 - 2n)E + 2E}{14r} = 3 \quad \text{(when aiding)}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
    \frac{(12 - 2n)E - 2E}{14r} = 2 \quad \text{(when opposing)}
\end{equation}

Solving these equations:

\begin{align*}
    (12 - 2n)E + 2E &= 42r \\
    (12 - 2n)E - 2E &= 28r
\end{align*}

Subtract the second equation from the first:

\begin{align*}
    [(12 - 2n)E + 2E] - [(12 - 2n)E - 2E] &= 42r - 28r \\
    4E &= 14r \\
    E &= \frac{7r}{2}
\end{align*}

Substitute \( E = \frac{7r}{2} \) into one of the original equations:

\begin{align*}
    (12 - 2n)\left(\frac{7r}{2}\right) + 2\left(\frac{7r}{2}\right) &= 42r \\
    (12 - 2n) \cdot \frac{7}{2} + 7 &= 42 \\
    42 - 7n + 7 &= 42 \\
    49 - 7n &= 42 \\
    7 &= 7n \\
    n &= 1
\end{align*}

Thus, the number of cells wrongly connected is \(\boxed{1}\).

\end{document}

