\begin{document}

\title{Physics Problem: Battery Charging}
\author{Indian Institute of Technology 1980}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem}

A battery of electromotive force $E = 2 \, \text{V}$ and internal resistance $r = 0.1 \, \Omega$ is being charged with a current of $I = 5 \, \text{A}$. In what direction will the current flow inside the battery? What is the potential difference between the two terminals of the battery?

\section*{Solution}

When a battery is being charged, the current flows into the positive terminal of the battery. Therefore, inside the battery, the current flows from the positive terminal to the negative terminal.

To find the potential difference between the two terminals of the battery, we use the formula for the terminal voltage $V$ of a battery being charged:

\[
V = E + Ir
\]

where:
\begin{align*}
E & = 2 \, \text{V} \quad \text{(electromotive force)}, \\
I & = 5 \, \text{A} \quad \text{(current)}, \\
r & = 0.1 \, \Omega \quad \text{(internal resistance)}.
\end{align*}

Substituting the given values into the equation, we have:

\[
V = 2 \, \text{V} + (5 \, \text{A})(0.1 \, \Omega) = 2 \, \text{V} + 0.5 \, \text{V} = 2.5 \, \text{V}
\]

Thus, the potential difference between the two terminals of the battery is $2.5 \, \text{V}$.

