First, calculate the equivalent resistance of the $5\,\Omega$ and $2\,\Omega$ resistors in parallel:

\[
R_{\text{parallel}} = \left(\frac{1}{5} + \frac{1}{2}\right)^{-1} = \left(\frac{2 + 5}{10}\right)^{-1} = \frac{10}{7}\,\Omega
\]

The total resistance in the circuit is then:

\[
R_{\text{total}} = 3\,\Omega + R_{\text{parallel}} = 3\,\Omega + \frac{10}{7}\,\Omega = \frac{31}{7}\,\Omega
\]

The total current supplied by the battery is:

\[
I_{\text{total}} = \frac{V}{R_{\text{total}}} = \frac{6\,\text{V}}{\frac{31}{7}\,\Omega} = \frac{42}{31}\,\text{A}
\]

The current through the $3\,\Omega$ resistor is the same as the total current:

\[
I_{3\Omega} = \frac{42}{31}\,\text{A}
\]

For the parallel resistors, the voltage across them is:

\[
V_{\text{parallel}} = I_{\text{total}} \times R_{\text{parallel}} = \frac{42}{31}\,\text{A} \times \frac{10}{7}\,\Omega = \frac{60}{31}\,\text{V}
\]

The current through the $5\,\Omega$ resistor is:

\[
I_{5\Omega} = \frac{V_{\text{parallel}}}{5\,\Omega} = \frac{60}{31}\,\text{V} \times \frac{1}{5}\,\Omega = \frac{12}{31}\,\text{A}
\]

The current through the $2\,\Omega$ resistor is:

\[
I_{2\Omega} = \frac{V_{\text{parallel}}}{2\,\Omega} = \frac{60}{31}\,\text{V} \times \frac{1}{2}\,\Omega = \frac{30}{31}\,\text{A}
\]

