\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\title{Physics Problem: EMF Calculation}
\author{Northern Universities of UK}
\date{}

\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

A uniform wire of length \(50 \, \text{cm}\) and resistance \(1 \, \Omega\) is connected to the terminals of an accumulator with an electromotive force (emf) of \(2.2 \, \text{V}\) and an internal resistance of \(0.1 \, \Omega\) (see Fig. 12.17). If the terminals of another cell can be connected to two points \(26 \, \text{cm}\) apart on the wire without altering the current in the wire, what is the emf of the cell?

\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{fig12_17.png} % Placeholder for the actual figure
    \caption{Schematic of the wire and accumulator setup.}
    \label{fig:12_17}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

Let's denote:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \(L = 50 \, \text{cm}\) as the total length of the wire.
    \item \(R = 1 \, \Omega\) as the total resistance of the wire.
    \item \(r = 0.1 \, \Omega\) as the internal resistance of the accumulator.
    \item \(V = 2.2 \, \text{V}\) as the emf of the accumulator.
    \item \(l = 26 \, \text{cm}\) as the length of the wire between the two points where the cell is connected.
\end{itemize}

The resistance of the wire segment between the two points is given by:
\[
R_{\text{segment}} = \frac{l}{L} \times R = \frac{26}{50} \times 1 \, \Omega = 0.52 \, \Omega
\]

The current \(I\) flowing through the circuit is given by Ohm's law:
\[
I = \frac{V}{R + r} = \frac{2.2}{1 + 0.1} = \frac{2.2}{1.1} = 2 \, \text{A}
\]

For the current in the wire to remain unchanged when the cell is connected, the potential difference across the \(26 \, \text{cm}\) segment must equal the emf of the cell. The potential difference across this segment is:
\[
V_{\text{segment}} = I \times R_{\text{segment}} = 2 \times 0.52 = 1.04 \, \text{V}
\]

Thus, the emf of the cell is:
\[
\boxed{1.04 \, \text{V}}
\]

\end{document}

