\section*{Meter Bridge Experiment Problem}

The balance point in a meter bridge experiment is obtained at 30 cm from the left. If the right-hand gap contains a resistance of \(3.5 \, \Omega\), what is the value of the resistance in the left-hand gap?

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{Fig12_20.png} % Replace with actual figure file if available
    \caption{Meter Bridge Setup}
    \label{fig:meter_bridge}
\end{figure}

\subsection*{Solution}

In a meter bridge experiment, the balance condition is given by the formula:

\[
\frac{R_1}{R_2} = \frac{l_1}{l_2}
\]

where \( R_1 \) is the resistance in the left-hand gap, \( R_2 = 3.5 \, \Omega \) is the resistance in the right-hand gap, \( l_1 = 30 \, \text{cm} \) is the length from the left to the balance point, and \( l_2 = 100 \, \text{cm} - l_1 = 70 \, \text{cm} \) is the length from the balance point to the right.

Substituting the known values into the equation, we have:

\[
\frac{R_1}{3.5} = \frac{30}{70}
\]

Solving for \( R_1 \):

\[
R_1 = 3.5 \times \frac{30}{70}
\]

\[
R_1 = 3.5 \times \frac{3}{7}
\]

\[
R_1 = 1.5 \, \Omega
\]

Therefore, the resistance in the left-hand gap is \( 1.5 \, \Omega \).

\end{document}

