\begin{document}

\title{Physics Problem: Voltmeter Reading}
\author{University of Oxford}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

A pocket voltmeter has a resistance of $120 \, \Omega$. What will it read when connected to a battery with an emf of $9 \, \text{V}$ and an internal resistance of $15 \, \Omega$?

\section*{Solution}

To find the reading of the voltmeter, we need to consider the circuit formed by the battery and the voltmeter. The total resistance in the circuit is the sum of the internal resistance of the battery and the resistance of the voltmeter:

\[
R_{\text{total}} = R_{\text{internal}} + R_{\text{voltmeter}} = 15 \, \Omega + 120 \, \Omega = 135 \, \Omega
\]

The current $I$ flowing through the circuit can be calculated using Ohm's Law:

\[
I = \frac{\text{emf}}{R_{\text{total}}} = \frac{9 \, \text{V}}{135 \, \Omega} = \frac{1}{15} \, \text{A}
\]

The voltage across the voltmeter, which is the reading of the voltmeter, is given by:

\[
V_{\text{voltmeter}} = I \times R_{\text{voltmeter}} = \left(\frac{1}{15} \, \text{A}\right) \times 120 \, \Omega = 8 \, \text{V}
\]

Therefore, the voltmeter will read $8 \, \text{V}$.

\end{document}

