\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{circuitikz}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

Calculate the current through the $3\,\Omega$ resistor and the power dissipated in the entire circuit shown in Fig. 12.22. The electromotive force (emf) of the battery is $1.8\,\text{V}$ and its internal resistance is $\frac{2}{3}\,\Omega$. [Indian Institute of Technology 1971]

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \begin{circuitikz}
        \draw
        (0,0) to[battery, l=$1.8\,\text{V}$] (0,4)
        to[R=$\frac{2}{3}\,\Omega$] (4,4)
        to[R=$3\,\Omega$] (4,0)
        -- (0,0);
    \end{circuitikz}
    \caption{Circuit Diagram}
    \label{fig:circuit}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

To find the current through the $3\,\Omega$ resistor, we first calculate the total resistance in the circuit. The total resistance $R_{\text{total}}$ is the sum of the internal resistance of the battery and the resistance of the $3\,\Omega$ resistor:

\[
R_{\text{total}} = \frac{2}{3}\,\Omega + 3\,\Omega = \frac{11}{3}\,\Omega
\]

Using Ohm's Law, the current $I$ through the circuit is given by:

\[
I = \frac{V}{R_{\text{total}}} = \frac{1.8\,\text{V}}{\frac{11}{3}\,\Omega} = \frac{1.8 \times 3}{11}\,\text{A} = \frac{5.4}{11}\,\text{A} \approx 0.491\,\text{A}
\]

Next, we calculate the power dissipated in the entire circuit. The power $P$ is given by:

\[
P = I^2 \times R_{\text{total}} = \left(\frac{5.4}{11}\right)^2 \times \frac{11}{3}\,\Omega
\]

Simplifying, we have:

\[
P = \frac{5.4^2}{11^2} \times \frac{11}{3} = \frac{29.16}{121} \times \frac{11}{3} = \frac{29.16 \times 11}{363} = \frac{320.76}{363} \approx 0.884\,\text{W}
\]

Thus, the current through the $3\,\Omega$ resistor is approximately $0.491\,\text{A}$, and the power dissipated in the entire circuit is approximately $0.884\,\text{W}$.

\end{document}

