\section*{Physics Problem and Solution}

A battery with electromotive force (emf) $\mathcal{E} = 24 \, \text{V}$ has an internal resistance $r = 0.02 \, \Omega$. A load resistor $R = 140 \, \Omega$ is connected to the terminals of the battery. 

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(i)] \textbf{Find the current flowing in the circuit under load conditions.}

    The total resistance in the circuit is the sum of the internal resistance and the load resistance:
    \[
    R_{\text{total}} = r + R = 0.02 \, \Omega + 140 \, \Omega = 140.02 \, \Omega
    \]

    Using Ohm's Law, the current $I$ flowing through the circuit is given by:
    \[
    I = \frac{\mathcal{E}}{R_{\text{total}}} = \frac{24 \, \text{V}}{140.02 \, \Omega} \approx 0.1714 \, \text{A}
    \]

    \item[(ii)] \textbf{Find the terminal voltage of the battery under load conditions.}

    The terminal voltage $V_{\text{terminal}}$ is given by:
    \[
    V_{\text{terminal}} = \mathcal{E} - I \cdot r = 24 \, \text{V} - (0.1714 \, \text{A} \times 0.02 \, \Omega) \approx 23.9966 \, \text{V}
    \]

    \item[(iii)] \textbf{Find the power dissipated in the resistor $R$ and in the battery's internal resistance $r$.}

    The power dissipated in the load resistor $R$ is:
    \[
    P_R = I^2 \cdot R = (0.1714 \, \text{A})^2 \times 140 \, \Omega \approx 4.114 \, \text{W}
    \]

    The power dissipated in the internal resistance $r$ is:
    \[
    P_r = I^2 \cdot r = (0.1714 \, \text{A})^2 \times 0.02 \, \Omega \approx 0.000588 \, \text{W}
    \]

    \item[(iv)] \textbf{Find the open circuit voltage of the battery under no load conditions and explain your answer.}

    The open circuit voltage of the battery is equal to the emf of the battery, as there is no current flowing through the internal resistance. Therefore, the open circuit voltage is:
    \[
    V_{\text{open}} = \mathcal{E} = 24 \, \text{V}
    \]

    This is because, under no load conditions, the internal resistance does not drop any voltage since the current is zero.

\end{enumerate}

\end{document}

