\section*{Kirchhoff's Rules}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Kirchhoff's Current Law (KCL):} The sum of currents entering a junction equals the sum of currents leaving the junction. Mathematically, this can be expressed as:
    \[
    \sum I_{\text{in}} = \sum I_{\text{out}}
    \]

    \item \textbf{Kirchhoff's Voltage Law (KVL):} The sum of the electromotive forces (emfs) and potential differences (voltage drops) around any closed loop in a circuit is zero. This can be written as:
    \[
    \sum \mathcal{E} - \sum IR = 0
    \]
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Application of Kirchhoff's Rules}

Consider the circuit shown in Fig. 12.26. We apply Kirchhoff's rules to obtain the following three equations for the unknown branch currents \(I_1\), \(I_2\), and \(I_3\):

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Applying KCL at junction \(A\):
    \[
    I_1 = I_2 + I_3
    \]

    \item Applying KVL to loop 1 (assuming clockwise direction):
    \[
    \mathcal{E}_1 - I_1 R_1 - I_2 R_2 = 0
    \]

    \item Applying KVL to loop 2 (assuming clockwise direction):
    \[
    \mathcal{E}_2 - I_3 R_3 - I_2 R_2 = 0
    \]
\end{enumerate}

