\title{Analysis of a Series-Parallel Resistive Circuit}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

Figure 12.27 shows a series-parallel resistive circuit connected to a DC supply. For the circuit shown, work out the following:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item The voltages $V_1$ and $V_2$ across resistors $R_1$ and $R_2$.
    \item The voltage $V_p$ across resistors $R_3$ and $R_4$.
    \item The currents $I_T$, $I_2$, and $I_3$.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{Figure12_27.png}
    \caption{Series-Parallel Resistive Circuit}
    \label{fig:12_27}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

To solve this problem, we will apply Ohm's Law and the rules for series and parallel circuits.

\subsection*{(i) Voltages $V_1$ and $V_2$}

Assuming the total voltage supplied by the DC source is $V_S$, the voltage across $R_1$ and $R_2$ can be calculated using the voltage division rule:

\[
V_1 = \frac{R_1}{R_1 + R_2} \cdot V_S
\]

\[
V_2 = \frac{R_2}{R_1 + R_2} \cdot V_S
\]

\subsection*{(ii) Voltage $V_p$}

Resistors $R_3$ and $R_4$ are in parallel, so the voltage across them is the same:

\[
V_p = V_1
\]

\subsection*{(iii) Currents $I_T$, $I_2$, and $I_3$}

The total current $I_T$ supplied by the source is:

\[
I_T = \frac{V_S}{R_{\text{total}}}
\]

where $R_{\text{total}}$ is the equivalent resistance of the circuit.

The current $I_2$ through $R_2$ is:

\[
I_2 = \frac{V_2}{R_2}
\]

The current $I_3$ through $R_3$ and $R_4$ (in parallel) is:

\[
I_3 = \frac{V_p}{R_3} = \frac{V_p}{R_4}
\]

\end{document}

