\title{Application of Kirchhoff's Rules}
\author{University of Aberystwyth, Wales 2006}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

Apply Kirchhoffs rules to the circuit shown in Fig. 12.28 to produce three equations with three unknown branch currents. You do not have to solve these equations for individual currents \(I\).

\section*{Solution}

Assume a circuit with three loops and three branch currents \(I_1\), \(I_2\), and \(I_3\). According to Kirchhoff's rules, we have:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Kirchhoff's Current Law (KCL):} At any junction, the sum of currents entering the junction equals the sum of currents leaving the junction.
    \item \textbf{Kirchhoff's Voltage Law (KVL):} The sum of the electromotive forces (emf) and potential differences (voltage drops) in any closed loop is zero.
\end{itemize}

Assuming the circuit has the following components and voltages:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \(R_1, R_2, R_3\) are the resistances in the circuit.
    \item \(E_1, E_2\) are the electromotive forces (batteries) in the circuit.
\end{itemize}

The equations based on Kirchhoff's rules are:

\begin{align}
    \text{Loop 1:} \quad & E_1 - I_1 R_1 - I_2 R_2 = 0, \\
    \text{Loop 2:} \quad & I_2 R_2 - I_3 R_3 - E_2 = 0, \\
    \text{Junction:} \quad & I_1 = I_2 + I_3.
\end{align}

These equations represent the application of Kirchhoff's rules to the circuit in Fig. 12.28. The unknowns \(I_1\), \(I_2\), and \(I_3\) can be solved using these equations.

\end{document}

