\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A singly charged particle of known velocity \( v = 2.5 \times 10^7 \, \si{m/s} \) but unknown mass moves in a bubble chamber in a circular path of radius \( r = 0.2 \, \si{m} \) in a field of \( B = 0.2 \, \si{T} \) acting perpendicular to the path. Determine the mass of the particle and identify it.

\section*{Solution}

The force acting on a charged particle moving in a magnetic field is given by the Lorentz force, which for circular motion is the centripetal force:

\[
F = qvB = \frac{mv^2}{r}
\]

where:
- \( q \) is the charge of the particle,
- \( v \) is the velocity of the particle,
- \( B \) is the magnetic field strength,
- \( m \) is the mass of the particle,
- \( r \) is the radius of the circular path.

Since the particle is singly charged, \( q = e \), where \( e = 1.6 \times 10^{-19} \, \si{C} \).

Rearranging the equation to solve for the mass \( m \):

\[
m = \frac{qBr}{v}
\]

Substituting the known values:

\[
m = \frac{(1.6 \times 10^{-19} \, \si{C})(0.2 \, \si{T})(0.2 \, \si{m})}{2.5 \times 10^7 \, \si{m/s}}
\]

Calculating the mass:

\[
m = \frac{6.4 \times 10^{-21} \, \si{C \cdot T \cdot m}}{2.5 \times 10^7 \, \si{m/s}} = 2.56 \times 10^{-28} \, \si{kg}
\]

The calculated mass \( m \approx 2.56 \times 10^{-28} \, \si{kg} \) is approximately equal to the mass of a proton, \( m_p \approx 1.67 \times 10^{-27} \, \si{kg} \). Therefore, the particle is likely a proton.

\end{document}

