\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Cyclotron Problem: Magnetic Field and Energy of Deuterons}

A cyclotron is powered by a \SI{50000}{\volt} \SI{5}{\mega\hertz} source. The diameter of the cyclotron is \SI{1.524}{\meter}. We need to find the magnetic field that satisfies the resonance condition for deuterons and the energies they will attain. The mass of a deuteron is given as \SI{2.0141}{\atomicmassunit}.

\subsection*{Resonance Condition for Cyclotron}

The resonance condition for a cyclotron is given by the equation:

\[
f = \frac{qB}{2\pi m}
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( f \) is the frequency of the cyclotron (\SI{5}{\mega\hertz}),
    \item \( q \) is the charge of the deuteron (\SI{1.602 \times 10^{-19}}{\coulomb}),
    \item \( B \) is the magnetic field,
    \item \( m \) is the mass of the deuteron.
\end{itemize}

The mass of the deuteron in kilograms is:

\[
m = 2.0141 \, \text{u} \times \SI{1.66053906660 \times 10^{-27}}{\kilogram/\atomicmassunit} = \SI{3.343583719 \times 10^{-27}}{\kilogram}
\]

Rearranging the resonance condition to solve for \( B \):

\[
B = \frac{2\pi m f}{q}
\]

Substituting the known values:

\[
B = \frac{2\pi \times \SI{3.343583719 \times 10^{-27}}{\kilogram} \times \SI{5 \times 10^{6}}{\hertz}}{\SI{1.602 \times 10^{-19}}{\coulomb}}
\]

\[
B \approx \SI{0.664}{\tesla}
\]

\subsection*{Energy Attained by Deuterons}

The maximum kinetic energy \( K \) attained by the deuterons is given by:

\[
K = qV
\]

where \( V \) is the potential difference (\SI{50000}{\volt}). Thus:

\[
K = \SI{1.602 \times 10^{-19}}{\coulomb} \times \SI{50000}{\volt} = \SI{8.01 \times 10^{-15}}{\joule}
\]

To convert this energy into electronvolts (eV):

\[
K = \frac{\SI{8.01 \times 10^{-15}}{\joule}}{\SI{1.602 \times 10^{-19}}{\joule/\electronvolt}} \approx \SI{50000}{\electronvolt} = \SI{50}{\kilo\electronvolt}
\]

\section*{Conclusion}

The magnetic field required to satisfy the resonance condition for deuterons in the cyclotron is approximately \SI{0.664}{\tesla}. The maximum energy attained by the deuterons is \SI{50}{\kilo\electronvolt}.

\end{document}

