\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

In the Bohr model of the hydrogen atom, the electron revolves in a circular orbit of radius \SI{0.53}{\angstrom} with a time period of \SI{1.5e-16}{\second}. Find the corresponding current.

\section*{Solution}

To find the current, we use the formula for current \( I \) due to a revolving charge:

\[
I = \frac{q}{T}
\]

where \( q \) is the charge of the electron and \( T \) is the time period of revolution.

Given:
\begin{align*}
q &= -e = -\SI{1.6e-19}{\coulomb}, \\
T &= \SI{1.5e-16}{\second}.
\end{align*}

The magnitude of the current is given by:

\[
I = \frac{\left| q \right|}{T} = \frac{\SI{1.6e-19}{\coulomb}}{\SI{1.5e-16}{\second}}
\]

Calculating the above expression:

\[
I = \frac{\SI{1.6e-19}{\coulomb}}{\SI{1.5e-16}{\second}} \approx \SI{1.07e-3}{\ampere}
\]

Thus, the corresponding current is approximately \SI{1.07}{\milli\ampere}.

\end{document}

