\begin{document}

\title{Magnetic Field Due to a Finite Straight Wire}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

Consider a current \( I \) flowing through a straight wire \( AB \) of finite length. We are interested in finding the magnetic field \( \mathbf{B} \) at a distance \( r \) from the wire, where the ends of the wire make inner angles \( \theta_1 \) and \( \theta_2 \) with the point \( P \), as shown in Fig. 13.3.

\section*{(a) Magnetic Field at a Distance \( r \)}

The magnetic field \( \mathbf{B} \) at a distance \( r \) from a finite straight wire carrying a current \( I \) can be determined using the Biot-Savart Law. The expression for the magnetic field is given by:

\[
\mathbf{B} = \frac{\mu_0 I}{4\pi r} \left( \sin \theta_1 + \sin \theta_2 \right)
\]

where:
- \( \mu_0 \) is the permeability of free space,
- \( \theta_1 \) and \( \theta_2 \) are the angles subtended by the ends of the wire at the point \( P \).

\section*{(b) Limit Value for a Very Long Wire}

For a very long wire, the angles \( \theta_1 \) and \( \theta_2 \) approach \( \frac{\pi}{2} \). In this limit, the expression for the magnetic field simplifies to:

\[
\mathbf{B} = \frac{\mu_0 I}{2\pi r}
\]

This is the well-known result for the magnetic field due to an infinitely long straight wire.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{figure13_3.png}
    \caption{Geometry for calculating the magnetic field at point \( P \) due to a finite straight wire \( AB \).}
    \label{fig:13_3}
\end{figure}

\end{document}

