\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] A current \( I \) is sent through a thin wire as in Fig. 13.6. The straight wires are very long and the radius of the curved part of the wire is \( R \). Show that the magnetic induction at the point \( O \) will be 
    \[
    B = \frac{\mu_0 I (\pi + 2)}{4 \pi R}
    \]
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth]{Fig13_6.png} % Placeholder for Fig. 13.6
    \end{center}

    \item[(b)] A wire shown in Fig. 13.7 carries current \( I \). Find the field of induction \( B \) at the centre \( O \).
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth]{Fig13_7.png} % Placeholder for Fig. 13.7
    \end{center}
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Magnetic Induction at Point O}

To find the magnetic induction at point \( O \), we consider the contribution from both the straight and curved segments of the wire.

1. **Straight Segments:**

   The magnetic field due to an infinitely long straight wire at a perpendicular distance \( R \) is given by:
   \[
   B_{\text{straight}} = \frac{\mu_0 I}{2 \pi R}
   \]
   Since there are two straight segments, the total contribution from the straight segments is:
   \[
   B_{\text{straight total}} = 2 \times \frac{\mu_0 I}{2 \pi R} = \frac{\mu_0 I}{\pi R}
   \]

2. **Curved Segment:**

   The magnetic field at the center of a circular arc of radius \( R \) and angle \( \theta = \pi \) (half-circle) is given by:
   \[
   B_{\text{arc}} = \frac{\mu_0 I \theta}{4 \pi R} = \frac{\mu_0 I \pi}{4 \pi R} = \frac{\mu_0 I}{4 R}
   \]

3. **Total Magnetic Induction:**

   Adding the contributions from the straight and curved segments:
   \[
   B = B_{\text{straight total}} + B_{\text{arc}} = \frac{\mu_0 I}{\pi R} + \frac{\mu_0 I}{4 R} = \frac{\mu_0 I (\pi + 2)}{4 \pi R}
   \]

\subsection*{(b) Magnetic Induction at the Centre O}

For the wire configuration shown in Fig. 13.7, the calculation of the magnetic field at the center \( O \) will depend on the specific geometry of the wire. Assuming it is a loop or a specific configuration, the Biot-Savart Law or Ampre's Law would be applied to determine \( B \).

\begin{center}
    \textit{(Further details would be provided based on the specific geometry of Fig. 13.7)}
\end{center}

\end{document}

