\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

Five hundred turns of a wire are wound on a thin tube 1 m long. If the wire carries a current of 5 A, determine the field in the tube.

\section*{Solution}

The magnetic field \( B \) inside a long solenoid is given by the formula:

\[
B = \mu_0 n I
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( \mu_0 \) is the permeability of free space, \( \mu_0 = 4\pi \times 10^{-7} \, \text{T}\cdot\text{m/A} \),
    \item \( n \) is the number of turns per unit length,
    \item \( I \) is the current in amperes.
\end{itemize}

Given:
\begin{align*}
    \text{Total number of turns } N &= 500, \\
    \text{Length of the solenoid } L &= 1 \, \text{m}, \\
    \text{Current } I &= 5 \, \text{A}.
\end{align*}

First, calculate the number of turns per unit length:
\[
n = \frac{N}{L} = \frac{500}{1} = 500 \, \text{turns/m}
\]

Now, substitute the values into the formula for the magnetic field:
\[
B = \mu_0 n I = (4\pi \times 10^{-7} \, \text{T}\cdot\text{m/A}) \times 500 \, \text{turns/m} \times 5 \, \text{A}
\]

Calculate \( B \):
\[
B = 4\pi \times 10^{-7} \times 500 \times 5
\]
\[
B = 10\pi \times 10^{-7} \, \text{T}
\]
\[
B = 10 \times 3.1416 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{T}
\]
\[
B \approx 3.1416 \times 10^{-6} \, \text{T}
\]

Thus, the magnetic field inside the tube is approximately \( 3.1416 \times 10^{-6} \, \text{T} \).

\end{document}

