\begin{document}

\title{Magnetic Field of a Hollow Copper Cylinder}
\author{}
\date{}

\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

A long hollow copper cylinder with inner radius $a$ and outer radius $b$ carries a current $I$. Calculate the magnitude of the magnetic field at a point $P$ where $a < r < b$ (see Fig. 13.10).

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{figure13_10.png} % Replace with actual figure file
    \caption{Illustration of the hollow copper cylinder with current $I$.}
    \label{fig:13_10}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

To find the magnetic field at a point $P$ inside the hollow region of the cylinder, we apply Ampre's Law:

\begin{equation}
    \oint \mathbf{B} \cdot d\mathbf{l} = \mu_0 I_{\text{enc}}
\end{equation}

where $\mathbf{B}$ is the magnetic field, $d\mathbf{l}$ is the differential length element along the path of integration, $\mu_0$ is the permeability of free space, and $I_{\text{enc}}$ is the current enclosed by the path of integration.

For a point $P$ at a distance $r$ from the axis of the cylinder, where $a < r < b$, the current enclosed $I_{\text{enc}}$ is zero because the current flows in the region $r > b$. Therefore, the magnetic field $\mathbf{B}$ at point $P$ is:

\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{B} = 0
\end{equation}

Thus, the magnitude of the magnetic field at point $P$ is zero.

\end{document}

