\begin{document}

\title{Helmholtz Coils Magnetic Field Calculation}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

Helmholtz coils consist of a pair of loops, each with $N$ turns and radius $R$. They are placed coaxially at distance $R$, and the same current $I$ flows through the loops but in the opposite sense. Show that the magnetic field at point $P$, midway between the centers $A$ and $C$, as shown in Fig. 13.11, is given by:

\begin{equation}
    B = \frac{8N\mu_0 I}{5^{3/2} R}
\end{equation}

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{figure_13_11.png} % Replace with actual figure path
    \caption{Configuration of Helmholtz Coils}
    \label{fig:helmholtz_coils}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

To derive the magnetic field at point $P$, we consider the contribution of the magnetic field due to each coil. The magnetic field at the center of a single loop with $N$ turns carrying current $I$ is given by:

\begin{equation}
    B_{\text{single}} = \frac{\mu_0 N I R^2}{2(R^2 + x^2)^{3/2}}
\end{equation}

where $x$ is the distance from the center of the loop to the point where the field is being calculated.

For Helmholtz coils, the point $P$ is located at $x = \frac{R}{2}$ from each coil. Thus, the magnetic field at $P$ due to one coil is:

\begin{equation}
    B_1 = \frac{\mu_0 N I R^2}{2\left(R^2 + \left(\frac{R}{2}\right)^2\right)^{3/2}}
\end{equation}

Simplifying the expression:

\begin{equation}
    B_1 = \frac{\mu_0 N I R^2}{2\left(\frac{5R^2}{4}\right)^{3/2}} = \frac{\mu_0 N I R^2}{2\left(\frac{5^{3/2} R^3}{8}\right)}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
    B_1 = \frac{4\mu_0 N I}{5^{3/2} R}
\end{equation}

Since the coils are identical and the current flows in opposite directions, the fields add up at point $P$:

\begin{equation}
    B = 2B_1 = \frac{8N\mu_0 I}{5^{3/2} R}
\end{equation}

Thus, the magnetic field at point $P$ is given by:

\begin{equation}
    B = \frac{8N\mu_0 I}{5^{3/2} R}
\end{equation}

This completes the solution.

\end{document}

