\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\title{Magnetic Field at the Center of Concentric Circular Arcs}
\author{University of Durham}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

Current $I$ flows in two concentric circular arcs of radii $r$ and $2r$, as shown in Fig. 13.12. Both arcs are quarters of a circle with point $P$ as the center. Determine the magnetic field $\mathbf{B}$ at point $P$.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \begin{tikzpicture}
        % Define the center
        \coordinate (P) at (0,0);

        % Draw the arcs
        \draw[thick] (0,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=90, radius=2];
        \draw[thick] (0,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=90, radius=1];

        % Label the center
        \node at (0,-0.2) {$P$};

        % Radii labels
        \draw[->] (0,0) -- (1,0.5) node[midway, above] {$r$};
        \draw[->] (0,0) -- (2,1) node[midway, above] {$2r$};
    \end{tikzpicture}
    \caption{Two concentric circular arcs with radii $r$ and $2r$.}
    \label{fig:13.12}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

The magnetic field at the center of a circular arc carrying current $I$ can be determined using the Biot-Savart Law. For a quarter-circle arc, the magnetic field at the center is given by:

\[
B = \frac{\mu_0 I}{4\pi R} \cdot \frac{\pi}{2} = \frac{\mu_0 I}{8R}
\]

where $R$ is the radius of the arc.

For the two arcs with radii $r$ and $2r$, the magnetic fields are:

\[
B_1 = \frac{\mu_0 I}{8r}
\]

\[
B_2 = \frac{\mu_0 I}{16r}
\]

Since both arcs contribute to the magnetic field in the same direction at point $P$, the total magnetic field $\mathbf{B}$ at point $P$ is:

\[
B = B_1 + B_2 = \frac{\mu_0 I}{8r} + \frac{\mu_0 I}{16r} = \frac{\mu_0 I}{8r} \left(1 + \frac{1}{2}\right) = \frac{3\mu_0 I}{16r}
\]

Thus, the magnetic field at point $P$ is:

\[
\boxed{\frac{3\mu_0 I}{16r}}
\]

\end{document}

