\begin{document}

\section*{Physics Problems and Solutions}

\subsection*{Problem (a)}

A current $I$ flows in a straight wire of length $L$. Show that the magnitude of the magnetic field at a perpendicular distance $x$ from the midpoint of the wire is given by 
\[
|B| = \frac{\mu_0 I}{4\pi} \frac{L}{x \sqrt{\left(\frac{L}{2}\right)^2 + x^2}}
\]
where $\mu_0$ is the permeability of free space. What is the direction of the $\mathbf{B}$ field?

\subsection*{Solution (a)}

To find the magnetic field at a distance $x$ from the midpoint of the wire, we use the Biot-Savart law:
\[
d\mathbf{B} = \frac{\mu_0 I}{4\pi} \frac{d\mathbf{l} \times \mathbf{r}}{r^3}
\]
where $d\mathbf{l}$ is an infinitesimal segment of the wire and $\mathbf{r}$ is the position vector from the segment to the point of interest. By integrating along the length of the wire and considering symmetry, we can derive the expression for $|B|$ as given above. The direction of the $\mathbf{B}$ field is determined by the right-hand rule, encircling the wire.

\subsection*{Problem (b)}

A loop of wire of length $l$ carries a current $I$. Compare the magnetic fields at the centre of the loop when it is bent into (a) a square and (b) an equilateral triangle.

\subsection*{Solution (b)}

\textbf{(a) Square Loop:}

For a square loop of side length $a = \frac{l}{4}$, the magnetic field at the center due to each side is given by:
\[
B_{\text{side}} = \frac{\mu_0 I}{4\pi} \frac{2}{a}
\]
The total magnetic field at the center is the vector sum of the fields due to all four sides:
\[
B_{\text{square}} = 4 \times B_{\text{side}} = \frac{\mu_0 I}{\pi a} = \frac{\mu_0 I}{\pi \frac{l}{4}} = \frac{4\mu_0 I}{\pi l}
\]

\textbf{(b) Equilateral Triangle:}

For an equilateral triangle with side length $a = \frac{l}{3}$, the magnetic field at the center due to each side is:
\[
B_{\text{side}} = \frac{\mu_0 I}{4\pi} \frac{\sqrt{3}}{a}
\]
The total magnetic field at the center is the vector sum of the fields due to all three sides:
\[
B_{\text{triangle}} = 3 \times B_{\text{side}} = \frac{3\sqrt{3}\mu_0 I}{4\pi a} = \frac{3\sqrt{3}\mu_0 I}{4\pi \frac{l}{3}} = \frac{9\sqrt{3}\mu_0 I}{4\pi l}
\]

Comparing the two, $B_{\text{triangle}}$ is greater than $B_{\text{square}}$ due to the geometry of the shapes.

\end{document}

