\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\title{Magnetic Field at the Midpoint Between Two Coaxial Coils}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

Two identical, parallel coaxial coils of radius $r$, each having $N$ turns, are separated by a distance $r$ along their common axis. They both carry a current $I$ in the same direction. Derive an expression for the magnetic field on the axis at the midpoint between the coils. Evaluate the field when $N = 100$, $r = \SI{20}{\centi\meter}$, and $I = \SI{2}{\ampere}$.

\section*{Solution}

The magnetic field at a point on the axis of a single circular coil of radius $r$ carrying a current $I$ with $N$ turns is given by the expression:

\[
B = \frac{\mu_0 N I r^2}{2 (r^2 + x^2)^{3/2}}
\]

where $x$ is the distance from the center of the coil to the point where the field is being calculated, and $\mu_0$ is the permeability of free space, $\mu_0 = 4\pi \times 10^{-7} \, \mathrm{T \cdot m/A}$.

For two identical coils separated by a distance $r$, the magnetic field at the midpoint (distance $x = r/2$ from each coil) is the sum of the fields due to each coil:

\[
B_{\text{total}} = 2 \times \frac{\mu_0 N I r^2}{2 \left( r^2 + \left(\frac{r}{2}\right)^2 \right)^{3/2}}
\]

Simplifying the expression:

\[
B_{\text{total}} = \frac{\mu_0 N I r^2}{\left( r^2 + \frac{r^2}{4} \right)^{3/2}} = \frac{\mu_0 N I r^2}{\left( \frac{5r^2}{4} \right)^{3/2}}
\]

\[
B_{\text{total}} = \frac{\mu_0 N I r^2}{\left( \frac{5^{3/2}r^3}{8} \right)} = \frac{8 \mu_0 N I}{5^{3/2} r}
\]

Now, substituting the given values $N = 100$, $r = \SI{0.2}{\meter}$, and $I = \SI{2}{\ampere}$:

\[
B_{\text{total}} = \frac{8 \times 4\pi \times 10^{-7} \times 100 \times 2}{5^{3/2} \times 0.2}
\]

\[
B_{\text{total}} = \frac{8 \times 4\pi \times 10^{-7} \times 200}{5^{3/2} \times 0.2}
\]

\[
B_{\text{total}} = \frac{6400\pi \times 10^{-7}}{5^{3/2} \times 0.2}
\]

Calculating the numerical value:

\[
B_{\text{total}} \approx \frac{6400\pi \times 10^{-7}}{11.18 \times 0.2} \approx \SI{2.26e-4}{\tesla}
\]

Thus, the magnetic field at the midpoint between the coils is approximately $\SI{2.26e-4}{\tesla}$.

\end{document}

