\begin{document}

\title{Order of Magnitude of Current Producing Earth's Magnetic Field}
\author{University of Manchester 1972}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem}

It is believed that the Earth's magnetic field is produced by circulating current in the core. If the mean radius of such currents is \SI{1000}{\kilo\meter}, what is the order of magnitude of current required to account for the Earth's dipolar magnetic field of magnitude \SI{6e-5}{\tesla} at the north magnetic pole?

\section*{Solution}

To estimate the current, we consider the magnetic field produced by a circular loop of current, which is analogous to the Earth's magnetic field. The magnetic field at the center of a circular loop of radius \( R \) carrying current \( I \) is given by:

\[
B = \frac{\mu_0 I}{2R}
\]

where \( \mu_0 = 4\pi \times 10^{-7} \, \si{\tesla \meter \per \ampere} \) is the permeability of free space.

Given:
\begin{align*}
B &= \SI{6e-5}{\tesla}, \\
R &= \SI{1000}{\kilo\meter} = \SI{1e6}{\meter}.
\end{align*}

Rearranging the formula to solve for \( I \), we have:

\[
I = \frac{2BR}{\mu_0}
\]

Substituting the given values:

\[
I = \frac{2 \times \SI{6e-5}{\tesla} \times \SI{1e6}{\meter}}{4\pi \times 10^{-7} \, \si{\tesla \meter \per \ampere}}
\]

Calculating the above expression:

\[
I \approx \frac{12 \times 10^{-5} \times 10^6}{4\pi \times 10^{-7}} \approx \frac{12 \times 10}{4\pi} \times 10^{8}
\]

\[
I \approx \frac{120}{12.56} \times 10^{8} \approx 9.55 \times 10^{8} \, \si{\ampere}
\]

Thus, the order of magnitude of the current required is approximately \( 10^9 \, \si{\ampere} \).

\end{document}

