\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{amssymb}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem Statement}

A conductor of length $1 \, \text{m}$ moves with a velocity given by $\mathbf{v} = (3\hat{\imath} + 2\hat{\jmath} + \hat{k}) \, \text{m/s}$ through a magnetic field given by $\mathbf{B} = (\hat{\imath} + 2\hat{\jmath} + 3\hat{k}) \, \text{Wb/m}^2$. How will the voltage developed across the ends of the conductor vary with its orientation? For what orientation will the voltage be zero? [University of Durham 1962]

\section*{Solution}

The voltage (emf) developed across the ends of the conductor is given by the formula:
\[
\mathcal{E} = \mathbf{v} \cdot (\mathbf{B} \times \mathbf{l})
\]
where $\mathbf{l}$ is the length vector of the conductor.

Since the conductor is $1 \, \text{m}$ long, we can consider $\mathbf{l}$ to be a unit vector in the direction of the conductor. The cross product $\mathbf{B} \times \mathbf{l}$ will depend on the orientation of $\mathbf{l}$.

The voltage will be zero when:
\[
\mathbf{v} \cdot (\mathbf{B} \times \mathbf{l}) = 0
\]

This condition is satisfied when $\mathbf{v}$ is parallel to $\mathbf{B} \times \mathbf{l}$, meaning the angle between $\mathbf{v}$ and $\mathbf{B} \times \mathbf{l}$ is $90^\circ$. Therefore, the voltage will be zero when the conductor is oriented such that $\mathbf{l}$ is parallel to $\mathbf{v}$ or $\mathbf{B}$, as this will make the cross product $\mathbf{B} \times \mathbf{l}$ zero.

\end{document}

