\section*{Problem}

A proton traveling with a velocity $\vec{v} = ( \hat{i} + 3 \hat{j} ) \times 10^4 \, \text{m/s}$ is located at $x = 2 \, \text{m}$ and $y = 3 \, \text{m}$ at some instant $t$. Calculate the magnetic field at time $t$ at the position $x = 2 \, \text{m}$, $y = 3 \, \text{m}$.

\section*{Solution}

To calculate the magnetic field $\vec{B}$ at the given position, we can use the Biot-Savart Law or other relevant equations depending on the context of the problem. However, since the problem does not provide additional information such as current or charge distribution, we will assume a general approach.

Assuming the presence of a magnetic field $\vec{B}$ due to the motion of the proton, the magnetic field can be calculated using the Lorentz force equation:

\[
\vec{F} = q (\vec{v} \times \vec{B})
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\vec{F}$ is the force experienced by the proton,
    \item $q$ is the charge of the proton, $q = +e = 1.602 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{C}$,
    \item $\vec{v}$ is the velocity of the proton, $\vec{v} = ( \hat{i} + 3 \hat{j} ) \times 10^4 \, \text{m/s}$,
    \item $\vec{B}$ is the magnetic field to be determined.
\end{itemize}

Since the problem does not specify the force or additional context, further assumptions or information would be required to solve for $\vec{B}$ explicitly.

\end{document}

