\begin{document}

\title{Force Between Parallel Current-Carrying Wires}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

Three long parallel wires, each carrying a current of \( I = \SI{20}{\ampere} \) in the same direction, are placed in the same plane with a spacing of \( d = \SI{10}{\centi\meter} \). Calculate the magnitude of the net force per meter on:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item an outer wire,
    \item the central wire.
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

The force per unit length between two parallel currents \( I_1 \) and \( I_2 \) separated by a distance \( d \) is given by the Ampre's force law:

\[
f = \frac{\mu_0 I_1 I_2}{2\pi d}
\]

where \( \mu_0 = 4\pi \times 10^{-7} \, \si{\tesla\meter\per\ampere} \) is the permeability of free space.

\subsection*{(a) Force on an Outer Wire}

Each outer wire experiences a force due to the central wire and the other outer wire. The forces due to the central wire and the other outer wire are in opposite directions.

The force per meter between an outer wire and the central wire is:

\[
f_{\text{outer-center}} = \frac{\mu_0 I^2}{2\pi d}
\]

The force per meter between the two outer wires is:

\[
f_{\text{outer-outer}} = \frac{\mu_0 I^2}{2\pi (2d)}
\]

The net force per meter on an outer wire is the difference between these two forces:

\[
f_{\text{net, outer}} = f_{\text{outer-center}} - f_{\text{outer-outer}} = \frac{\mu_0 I^2}{2\pi d} - \frac{\mu_0 I^2}{2\pi (2d)}
\]

Simplifying, we get:

\[
f_{\text{net, outer}} = \frac{\mu_0 I^2}{2\pi d} \left(1 - \frac{1}{2}\right) = \frac{\mu_0 I^2}{4\pi d}
\]

Substituting the known values:

\[
f_{\text{net, outer}} = \frac{4\pi \times 10^{-7} \times (20)^2}{4\pi \times 0.1} = \SI{4e-4}{\newton\per\meter}
\]

\subsection*{(b) Force on the Central Wire}

The central wire experiences forces due to both outer wires, which are equal in magnitude and opposite in direction. Thus, the net force on the central wire is zero:

\[
f_{\text{net, center}} = f_{\text{outer-center}} - f_{\text{outer-center}} = 0
\]

Therefore, the net force per meter on the central wire is \(\SI{0}{\newton\per\meter}\).

\end{document}

