\begin{document}

\title{Physics Problem: Motion of a Conducting Rod in a Magnetic Field}
\author{University of Durham}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

Two parallel rails of negligible resistance are at distance $d$ apart and are connected by a resistor of resistance $R$. A conducting rod lies perpendicular to the two rails and is free to slide on the rails. A constant magnetic field $B$ is perpendicular to the loop formed by the rails, rod, and resistor. An external agent drags the rod at velocity $v$ along the rails. Find:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The current flowing in the resistor.
    \item The total power delivered to the resistor.
    \item The magnitude of the applied force that is needed to move the rod with this velocity.
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Current Flowing in the Resistor}

The induced electromotive force (emf) $\mathcal{E}$ in the loop is given by Faraday's law of electromagnetic induction:
\[
\mathcal{E} = B \cdot v \cdot d
\]
where $B$ is the magnetic field, $v$ is the velocity of the rod, and $d$ is the distance between the rails.

The current $I$ flowing through the resistor is given by Ohm's law:
\[
I = \frac{\mathcal{E}}{R} = \frac{Bvd}{R}
\]

\subsection*{(b) Total Power Delivered to the Resistor}

The power $P$ delivered to the resistor is given by:
\[
P = I^2 R = \left(\frac{Bvd}{R}\right)^2 R = \frac{(Bvd)^2}{R}
\]

\subsection*{(c) Magnitude of the Applied Force}

The magnetic force $F_{\text{mag}}$ on the rod, which is equal in magnitude and opposite in direction to the applied force $F_{\text{app}}$, is given by:
\[
F_{\text{mag}} = I \cdot B \cdot d = \frac{Bvd}{R} \cdot B \cdot d = \frac{B^2 v d^2}{R}
\]

Therefore, the magnitude of the applied force needed to move the rod with velocity $v$ is:
\[
F_{\text{app}} = \frac{B^2 v d^2}{R}
\]

\end{document}

