\begin{document}

\section*{Calculation of Energy Density at the Centre of a Circular Loop}

To calculate the energy density at the center of a circular loop of wire, we first determine the magnetic field at the center. The magnetic field \( B \) at the center of a circular loop carrying a current \( I \) is given by:

\[
B = \frac{\mu_0 I}{2R}
\]

where \( \mu_0 \) is the permeability of free space (\( \mu_0 = 4\pi \times 10^{-7} \, \text{T}\cdot\text{m/A} \)), \( I \) is the current, and \( R \) is the radius of the loop.

The energy density \( u \) of the magnetic field is given by:

\[
u = \frac{B^2}{2\mu_0}
\]

Given:
\begin{align*}
R &= 10 \, \text{cm} = 0.1 \, \text{m}, \\
I &= 100 \, \text{A}
\end{align*}

\subsection*{Step 1: Calculate the Magnetic Field \( B \)}

\[
B = \frac{\mu_0 I}{2R} = \frac{4\pi \times 10^{-7} \times 100}{2 \times 0.1} = 2\pi \times 10^{-4} \, \text{T}
\]

\subsection*{Step 2: Calculate the Energy Density \( u \)}

\[
u = \frac{B^2}{2\mu_0} = \frac{(2\pi \times 10^{-4})^2}{2 \times 4\pi \times 10^{-7}} = \frac{4\pi^2 \times 10^{-8}}{8\pi \times 10^{-7}} = \frac{\pi}{2} \times 10^{-1} \, \text{J/m}^3
\]

Thus, the energy density at the center of the loop is approximately \( \frac{\pi}{2} \times 10^{-1} \, \text{J/m}^3 \).

\end{document}

