\section*{Physics Problem}

Consider a bar sliding on rails separated by 20 cm, as shown in Figure 13.17. If the current flowing through the resistor $R = 5 \, \Omega$ is $0.4 \, \text{A}$ and the magnetic field $B = 1 \, \text{T}$, what is the speed of the bar?

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{figure13_17.png} % Replace with actual figure file
    \caption{Figure 13.17: Bar sliding on rails.}
    \label{fig:13_17}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

To find the speed of the bar, we can use the formula for the electromotive force (emf) induced in the bar due to its motion in a magnetic field:

\[
\text{emf} = B \cdot v \cdot L
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $B = 1 \, \text{T}$ is the magnetic field,
    \item $v$ is the speed of the bar,
    \item $L = 0.2 \, \text{m}$ is the separation between the rails.
\end{itemize}

The induced emf is also equal to the voltage across the resistor, which can be calculated using Ohm's Law:

\[
V = I \cdot R = 0.4 \, \text{A} \times 5 \, \Omega = 2 \, \text{V}
\]

Setting the expressions for the emf equal gives:

\[
B \cdot v \cdot L = 2 \, \text{V}
\]

Solving for $v$, we have:

\[
v = \frac{2 \, \text{V}}{B \cdot L} = \frac{2 \, \text{V}}{1 \, \text{T} \cdot 0.2 \, \text{m}} = 10 \, \text{m/s}
\]

Thus, the speed of the bar is $10 \, \text{m/s}$.

\end{document}

