\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

The Hall coefficient and electrical conductivity of an n-type silicon are \(-7.3 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{m}^3/\text{C}\) and \(2 \times 10^7 \, \text{mho/m}\), respectively. Calculate the magnitude of the mobility of the electrons. [University of Durham 1962]

\section*{Solution}

The mobility \(\mu\) of the electrons can be calculated using the relation between the Hall coefficient \(R_H\), electrical conductivity \(\sigma\), and mobility \(\mu\):

\[
\mu = \sigma \cdot |R_H|
\]

Substituting the given values:

\[
\mu = 2 \times 10^7 \, \text{mho/m} \times 7.3 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{m}^3/\text{C}
\]

\[
\mu = 1.46 \, \text{m}^2/\text{V}\cdot\text{s}
\]

\section*{Additional Calculations}

\subsection*{13.1104G = 1T}

The frequency \(f\) is given by:

\[
f = \frac{Bq}{2\pi m} = \frac{1 \times 1.6 \times 10^{-19}}{2\pi \times 4.0026 \times 1.66 \times 10^{-27}}
\]

\[
f = 3.83 \times 10^6 \, \text{Hz} = 3.83 \, \text{MHz}
\]

\subsection*{13.2(a)}

The kinetic energy \(K_p\) is given by:

\[
K_p = \frac{1}{2} q^2 r^2 B^2 / m_p = \frac{1}{2} \times (1.6 \times 10^{-19})^2 \times (0.25)^2 \times (1.5)^2 / 1.66 \times 10^{-27}
\]

\[
K_p = 2.17 \times 10^{-13} \, \text{J} = 2.17 \times 10^{-12} \, \text{J} \times \frac{1}{1.6 \times 10^{-13} \, \text{MeV/J}}
\]

\[
K_p = 13.56 \, \text{MeV}
\]

\end{document}

