\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem A2}

A \(2.5 \, \mu\text{F}\) capacitor is connected in series with a non-inductive resistor of \(300 \, \Omega\) across a source of potential difference (PD) of rms value \(50 \, \text{V}\), alternating at \(\frac{1000}{2\pi} \, \text{Hz}\). Calculate:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] The thermal values of the current in the circuit and the PD across the capacitor.
    \item[(b)] The mean rate at which the energy is supplied by the source.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection*{Solution}

\subsubsection*{(a) Thermal Values of the Current and PD across the Capacitor}

The angular frequency \(\omega\) is given by:
\[
\omega = 2\pi f = 1000 \, \text{rad/s}
\]

The capacitive reactance \(X_C\) is:
\[
X_C = \frac{1}{\omega C} = \frac{1}{1000 \times 2.5 \times 10^{-6}} = 400 \, \Omega
\]

The total impedance \(Z\) of the circuit is:
\[
Z = \sqrt{R^2 + X_C^2} = \sqrt{300^2 + 400^2} = 500 \, \Omega
\]

The rms current \(I\) in the circuit is:
\[
I = \frac{V_{\text{rms}}}{Z} = \frac{50}{500} = 0.1 \, \text{A}
\]

The PD across the capacitor \(V_C\) is:
\[
V_C = I \times X_C = 0.1 \times 400 = 40 \, \text{V}
\]

\subsubsection*{(b) Mean Rate of Energy Supplied by the Source}

The mean power \(P\) supplied by the source is given by:
\[
P = I^2 R = (0.1)^2 \times 300 = 3 \, \text{W}
\]

\end{document}

