\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

An inductance stores 10 J of energy when the current is 5 A. Find its value.

\section*{Solution}

The energy stored in an inductor is given by the formula:

\[
E = \frac{1}{2} L I^2
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( E \) is the energy stored in the inductor (in joules),
    \item \( L \) is the inductance (in henrys),
    \item \( I \) is the current (in amperes).
\end{itemize}

Given:
\begin{align*}
    E &= 10 \, \text{J} \\
    I &= 5 \, \text{A}
\end{align*}

We need to find the inductance \( L \). Rearrange the formula to solve for \( L \):

\[
L = \frac{2E}{I^2}
\]

Substitute the given values into the equation:

\[
L = \frac{2 \times 10 \, \text{J}}{(5 \, \text{A})^2}
\]

Calculate:

\[
L = \frac{20}{25} = 0.8 \, \text{H}
\]

Thus, the inductance is \( L = 0.8 \, \text{H}.

\end{document}

