\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A \(6 \, \Omega\) resistor, a \(12 \, \Omega\) inductive reactance, and a \(20 \, \Omega\) capacitive reactance are connected in series to a \(250 \, \text{V}_{\text{rms}}\) AC generator. 

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] Find the impedance.
    \item[(b)] Estimate the power dissipated in the resistor.
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] The impedance \( Z \) of a series RLC circuit is given by:
    \[
    Z = \sqrt{R^2 + (X_L - X_C)^2}
    \]
    where \( R = 6 \, \Omega \), \( X_L = 12 \, \Omega \), and \( X_C = 20 \, \Omega \).

    Substituting the given values:
    \[
    Z = \sqrt{6^2 + (12 - 20)^2} = \sqrt{36 + (-8)^2} = \sqrt{36 + 64} = \sqrt{100} = 10 \, \Omega
    \]

    \item[(b)] The power dissipated in the resistor is given by:
    \[
    P = I^2 R
    \]
    where \( I \) is the current through the circuit. The current \( I \) can be found using Ohm's law for AC circuits:
    \[
    I = \frac{V_{\text{rms}}}{Z} = \frac{250 \, \text{V}}{10 \, \Omega} = 25 \, \text{A}
    \]

    Thus, the power dissipated in the resistor is:
    \[
    P = (25 \, \text{A})^2 \times 6 \, \Omega = 625 \times 6 = 3750 \, \text{W}
    \]
\end{enumerate}

\end{document}

