\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

A capacitor has a reactance of \(4 \, \Omega\) at \SI{250}{\hertz}. 

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] Find the capacitance.
    \item[(b)] Calculate the reactance at \SI{100}{\hertz}.
    \item[(c)] What is the rms current, if it is connected to a \SI{220}{\volt} \SI{50}{\hertz} line?
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Find the Capacitance}

The reactance \(X_C\) of a capacitor is given by the formula:
\[
X_C = \frac{1}{2\pi f C}
\]
where \(f\) is the frequency and \(C\) is the capacitance. Given that \(X_C = 4 \, \Omega\) at \(f = \SI{250}{\hertz}\), we can solve for \(C\):
\[
4 = \frac{1}{2\pi \times 250 \times C}
\]
\[
C = \frac{1}{2\pi \times 250 \times 4}
\]
\[
C \approx \SI{159.15}{\micro\farad}
\]

\subsection*{(b) Calculate the Reactance at \SI{100}{\hertz}}

Using the capacitance found in part (a), calculate the reactance at \SI{100}{\hertz}:
\[
X_C = \frac{1}{2\pi \times 100 \times C}
\]
Substituting \(C \approx \SI{159.15}{\micro\farad}\):
\[
X_C = \frac{1}{2\pi \times 100 \times 159.15 \times 10^{-6}}
\]
\[
X_C \approx \SI{10}{\ohm}
\]

\subsection*{(c) RMS Current with a \SI{220}{\volt} \SI{50}{\hertz} Line}

First, calculate the reactance at \SI{50}{\hertz}:
\[
X_C = \frac{1}{2\pi \times 50 \times C}
\]
\[
X_C = \frac{1}{2\pi \times 50 \times 159.15 \times 10^{-6}}
\]
\[
X_C \approx \SI{20}{\ohm}
\]

The rms current \(I_{\text{rms}}\) is given by Ohm's Law:
\[
I_{\text{rms}} = \frac{V_{\text{rms}}}{X_C}
\]
where \(V_{\text{rms}} = \SI{220}{\volt}\):
\[
I_{\text{rms}} = \frac{220}{20}
\]
\[
I_{\text{rms}} = \SI{11}{\ampere}
\]

\end{document}

