\section*{Problem}

When a 0.6 H inductor is connected to a 220 V 50 Hz AC line, what is (a) the rms current and (b) peak current?

\section*{Solution}

Given:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Inductance, $L = 0.6\, \text{H}$
    \item Voltage, $V_{\text{rms}} = 220\, \text{V}$
    \item Frequency, $f = 50\, \text{Hz}$
\end{itemize}

The inductive reactance $X_L$ is given by:
\[
X_L = 2 \pi f L
\]

Substituting the given values:
\[
X_L = 2 \pi \times 50 \times 0.6 = 60 \pi\, \Omega
\]

(a) The rms current $I_{\text{rms}}$ can be calculated using Ohm's Law for AC circuits:
\[
I_{\text{rms}} = \frac{V_{\text{rms}}}{X_L}
\]

Substitute the known values:
\[
I_{\text{rms}} = \frac{220}{60 \pi} \approx 1.166\, \text{A}
\]

(b) The peak current $I_{\text{peak}}$ is related to the rms current by the following relation:
\[
I_{\text{peak}} = I_{\text{rms}} \times \sqrt{2}
\]

Substitute the value of $I_{\text{rms}}$:
\[
I_{\text{peak}} = 1.166 \times \sqrt{2} \approx 1.649\, \text{A}
\]

Thus, the rms current is approximately $1.166\, \text{A}$ and the peak current is approximately $1.649\, \text{A}$.

\end{document}

