\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

Show that in the usual notation the following combinations of physical quantities have the units of time:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] $RC$
    \item[(b)] $\frac{L}{R}$
    \item[(c)] $\sqrt{LC}$
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

To show that each expression has the units of time, we will analyze the units of resistance ($R$), capacitance ($C$), and inductance ($L$).

\begin{itemize}
    \item Resistance, $R$, has units of ohms ($\Omega$), which can be expressed in terms of fundamental units as $\text{kg} \cdot \text{m}^2 \cdot \text{s}^{-3} \cdot \text{A}^{-2}$.
    \item Capacitance, $C$, has units of farads (F), which can be expressed as $\text{s}^4 \cdot \text{A}^2 \cdot \text{m}^{-2} \cdot \text{kg}^{-1}$.
    \item Inductance, $L$, has units of henrys (H), which can be expressed as $\text{kg} \cdot \text{m}^2 \cdot \text{s}^{-2} \cdot \text{A}^{-2}$.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{(a) $RC$}

The units of $RC$ are given by:
\[
RC = \left( \text{kg} \cdot \text{m}^2 \cdot \text{s}^{-3} \cdot \text{A}^{-2} \right) \left( \text{s}^4 \cdot \text{A}^2 \cdot \text{m}^{-2} \cdot \text{kg}^{-1} \right)
\]

Simplifying, we get:
\[
RC = \text{s}
\]

Thus, $RC$ has the units of time.

\subsection*{(b) $\frac{L}{R}$}

The units of $\frac{L}{R}$ are given by:
\[
\frac{L}{R} = \frac{\text{kg} \cdot \text{m}^2 \cdot \text{s}^{-2} \cdot \text{A}^{-2}}{\text{kg} \cdot \text{m}^2 \cdot \text{s}^{-3} \cdot \text{A}^{-2}}
\]

Simplifying, we get:
\[
\frac{L}{R} = \text{s}
\]

Thus, $\frac{L}{R}$ has the units of time.

\subsection*{(c) $\sqrt{LC}$}

The units of $\sqrt{LC}$ are given by:
\[
\sqrt{LC} = \sqrt{\left( \text{kg} \cdot \text{m}^2 \cdot \text{s}^{-2} \cdot \text{A}^{-2} \right) \left( \text{s}^4 \cdot \text{A}^2 \cdot \text{m}^{-2} \cdot \text{kg}^{-1} \right)}
\]

Simplifying, we get:
\[
\sqrt{LC} = \sqrt{\text{s}^2} = \text{s}
\]

Thus, $\sqrt{LC}$ has the units of time.

\end{document}

