\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{amssymb}

\begin{document}

For the electrical circuit shown below, when the switch $K$ is closed, the charge and current are observed to oscillate (Fig. 14.2). Show that the differential equation governing the charge of the system can be written as:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{d^2Q}{dt^2} + 2\gamma \frac{dQ}{dt} + \omega_0^2 Q = 0
\end{equation}

where $\gamma$ and $\omega_0^2$ are to be determined in terms of the capacitance $C$, inductance $L$, and resistance $R$.

For a resistance $R = 100 \, \Omega$, capacitance $C = 700 \, \text{pF}$, and inductance $L = 80 \, \text{mH}$, calculate:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] The natural frequency, $f_0$, of the oscillation.
    \item[(b)] The time constant, $\tau$, for the decay.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Solution:}

The differential equation for an RLC circuit is given by:

\begin{equation}
    L \frac{d^2Q}{dt^2} + R \frac{dQ}{dt} + \frac{Q}{C} = 0
\end{equation}

Comparing this with the standard form:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{d^2Q}{dt^2} + 2\gamma \frac{dQ}{dt} + \omega_0^2 Q = 0
\end{equation}

we identify:

\begin{align*}
    2\gamma &= \frac{R}{L} \\
    \omega_0^2 &= \frac{1}{LC}
\end{align*}

Substituting the given values:

\begin{align*}
    R &= 100 \, \Omega \\
    C &= 700 \, \text{pF} = 700 \times 10^{-12} \, \text{F} \\
    L &= 80 \, \text{mH} = 80 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{H}
\end{align*}

Calculate $\gamma$ and $\omega_0$:

\begin{align*}
    \gamma &= \frac{R}{2L} = \frac{100}{2 \times 80 \times 10^{-3}} = \frac{100}{160 \times 10^{-3}} = 625 \, \text{s}^{-1} \\
    \omega_0 &= \sqrt{\frac{1}{LC}} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{80 \times 10^{-3} \times 700 \times 10^{-12}}} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{56 \times 10^{-12}}} \approx 13333 \, \text{rad/s}
\end{align*}

(a) The natural frequency $f_0$ is given by:

\begin{equation}
    f_0 = \frac{\omega_0}{2\pi} \approx \frac{13333}{2\pi} \approx 2122 \, \text{Hz}
\end{equation}

(b) The time constant $\tau$ for the decay is:

\begin{equation}
    \tau = \frac{1}{\gamma} = \frac{1}{625} \approx 1.6 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{s}
\end{equation}

\end{document}

