\begin{document}

\title{Physics Problem: Inductance and Capacitance}
\author{University of Manchester 1972}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

An inductance and condenser in series have a capacitive impedance of $500 \, \Omega$ at $1 \, \text{kHz}$ and an inductive impedance of $100 \, \Omega$ at $5 \, \text{kHz}$. Find the values of inductance and capacitance.

\section*{Solution}

To solve this problem, we need to use the formulas for capacitive and inductive reactance:

\begin{align*}
    X_C &= \frac{1}{2 \pi f C}, \\
    X_L &= 2 \pi f L,
\end{align*}

where $X_C$ is the capacitive reactance, $X_L$ is the inductive reactance, $f$ is the frequency, $C$ is the capacitance, and $L$ is the inductance.

Given:
\begin{align*}
    X_C &= 500 \, \Omega \quad \text{at} \quad f = 1 \, \text{kHz}, \\
    X_L &= 100 \, \Omega \quad \text{at} \quad f = 5 \, \text{kHz}.
\end{align*}

First, calculate the capacitance $C$:
\begin{align*}
    500 &= \frac{1}{2 \pi (1 \times 10^3) C}, \\
    C &= \frac{1}{2 \pi (1 \times 10^3) \cdot 500}.
\end{align*}

Now, calculate the inductance $L$:
\begin{align*}
    100 &= 2 \pi (5 \times 10^3) L, \\
    L &= \frac{100}{2 \pi (5 \times 10^3)}.
\end{align*}

Thus, the values of inductance and capacitance are:
\begin{align*}
    C &= \frac{1}{2 \pi \times 10^3 \times 500} \, \text{F}, \\
    L &= \frac{100}{2 \pi \times 5 \times 10^3} \, \text{H}.
\end{align*}

\end{document}

