\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A condenser of $0.01 \, \mu\text{F}$ is charged to $100 \, \text{V}$. Calculate the peak current that flows when the charged condenser is connected across an inductance of $10 \, \text{mH}$. [University of Manchester 1972]

\section*{Solution}

The peak current in an LC circuit can be calculated using the formula for the resonant angular frequency $\omega_0$ and the maximum current $I_{\text{max}}$:

\[
\omega_0 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{LC}}
\]

where:
\begin{align*}
L &= 10 \, \text{mH} = 10 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{H}, \\
C &= 0.01 \, \mu\text{F} = 0.01 \times 10^{-6} \, \text{F}.
\end{align*}

Substituting the values of $L$ and $C$ into the formula for $\omega_0$:

\[
\omega_0 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{(10 \times 10^{-3}) \times (0.01 \times 10^{-6})}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{10^{-10}}} = 10^5 \, \text{rad/s}
\]

The peak current $I_{\text{max}}$ is given by:

\[
I_{\text{max}} = C \cdot V \cdot \omega_0
\]

Substituting the values:

\[
I_{\text{max}} = (0.01 \times 10^{-6}) \cdot 100 \cdot 10^5 = 0.01 \, \text{A} = 10 \, \text{mA}
\]

Therefore, the peak current that flows is $10 \, \text{mA}$.

\end{document}

