\begin{document}

\title{Parallel Resonant Circuit Analysis}
\author{University of Manchester 1972}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

A parallel resonant circuit consists of a coil with inductance \( L = \SI{1}{\milli\henry} \) and resistance \( R = \SI{10}{\ohm} \) in parallel with a capacitance \( C = \SI{0.0005}{\micro\farad} \). Calculate the resonant frequency and the quality factor \( Q \) of the circuit.

\section*{Solution}

The resonant frequency \( f_0 \) of a parallel LC circuit is given by the formula:

\[
f_0 = \frac{1}{2\pi\sqrt{LC}}
\]

Substituting the given values:

\[
L = \SI{1}{\milli\henry} = \SI{1e-3}{\henry}, \quad C = \SI{0.0005}{\micro\farad} = \SI{0.5e-9}{\farad}
\]

\[
f_0 = \frac{1}{2\pi\sqrt{(1 \times 10^{-3})(0.5 \times 10^{-9})}}
\]

\[
f_0 = \frac{1}{2\pi\sqrt{0.5 \times 10^{-12}}}
\]

\[
f_0 = \frac{1}{2\pi \times 0.7071 \times 10^{-6}}
\]

\[
f_0 \approx \SI{225.08}{\kilo\hertz}
\]

The quality factor \( Q \) for a parallel resonant circuit is given by:

\[
Q = \frac{R}{\omega_0 L}
\]

where \( \omega_0 = 2\pi f_0 \).

\[
\omega_0 = 2\pi \times \SI{225.08e3}{\hertz}
\]

\[
Q = \frac{10}{2\pi \times 225.08 \times 10^3 \times 1 \times 10^{-3}}
\]

\[
Q \approx \frac{10}{1414.16}
\]

\[
Q \approx 7.07
\]

Thus, the resonant frequency is approximately \(\SI{225.08}{\kilo\hertz}\) and the quality factor \( Q \) is approximately \( 7.07 \).

\end{document}

