\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

The voltage on a capacitor in a certain circuit is given by:

\begin{equation}
    V(t) = V_0 e^{-t/RC}
\end{equation}

We need to find the fractional error in the voltage at \( t = 50 \, \mu\text{s} \) if \( R = 50 \, \text{k}\Omega \pm 5\% \) and \( C = 0.01 \, \mu\text{F} \pm 10\% \).

The fractional error in \( V(t) \) can be determined using the formula for the propagation of uncertainty:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{\Delta V}{V} = \sqrt{\left(\frac{\Delta R}{R}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{\Delta C}{C}\right)^2}
\end{equation}

Given:
\begin{align*}
    R &= 50 \, \text{k}\Omega \quad \text{with} \quad \frac{\Delta R}{R} = 0.05, \\
    C &= 0.01 \, \mu\text{F} \quad \text{with} \quad \frac{\Delta C}{C} = 0.10.
\end{align*}

Substituting these values into the fractional error formula:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{\Delta V}{V} = \sqrt{(0.05)^2 + (0.10)^2} = \sqrt{0.0025 + 0.01} = \sqrt{0.0125} \approx 0.1118
\end{equation}

Thus, the fractional error in the voltage at \( t = 50 \, \mu\text{s} \) is approximately 11.18\%.

\end{document}

