\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\title{Physics Problem: Discharging a Capacitor through a Resistor}
\author{University of Manchester 1958}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

A condenser of \SI{10}{\micro\farad} capacitance is charged to \SI{3000}{\volt} and then discharged through a resistor of \SI{10000}{\ohm}. If the resistor has a temperature coefficient of \SI{0.004}{/\degreeCelsius} and a thermal capacity of \SI{0.9}{\calorie/\degreeCelsius}, find:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] the time taken for the voltage on the condenser to fall to $1/e$ of its initial value;
    \item[(b)] the percentage error which would have been introduced if thermal effects had been ignored.
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Time Constant Calculation}

The time constant $\tau$ for an RC circuit is given by:
\[
\tau = R \cdot C
\]
where $R = \SI{10000}{\ohm}$ and $C = \SI{10}{\micro\farad} = \SI{10e-6}{\farad}$.

\[
\tau = \SI{10000}{\ohm} \times \SI{10e-6}{\farad} = \SI{0.1}{\second}
\]

The voltage $V(t)$ across the capacitor as a function of time is given by:
\[
V(t) = V_0 e^{-t/\tau}
\]
where $V_0 = \SI{3000}{\volt}$.

To find the time $t$ when the voltage falls to $1/e$ of its initial value:
\[
V(t) = \frac{V_0}{e} \Rightarrow e^{-t/\tau} = \frac{1}{e}
\]
\[
t = \tau = \SI{0.1}{\second}
\]

\subsection*{(b) Percentage Error Due to Ignoring Thermal Effects}

The resistance $R$ changes with temperature, which affects the time constant. The change in resistance $\Delta R$ due to a temperature change $\Delta T$ is given by:
\[
\Delta R = R \cdot \alpha \cdot \Delta T
\]
where $\alpha = \SI{0.004}{/\degreeCelsius}$.

The energy dissipated in the resistor is:
\[
E = \frac{1}{2} C V_0^2 = \frac{1}{2} \times \SI{10e-6}{\farad} \times (\SI{3000}{\volt})^2 = \SI{45}{\joule}
\]

Converting energy to calories (since \SI{1}{\joule} = \SI{0.239}{\calorie}):
\[
E = \SI{45}{\joule} \times \SI{0.239}{\calorie/\joule} = \SI{10.755}{\calorie}
\]

The temperature rise $\Delta T$ is:
\[
\Delta T = \frac{E}{C_{\text{thermal}}} = \frac{\SI{10.755}{\calorie}}{\SI{0.9}{\calorie/\degreeCelsius}} \approx \SI{11.95}{\degreeCelsius}
\]

The change in resistance $\Delta R$ is:
\[
\Delta R = \SI{10000}{\ohm} \times \SI{0.004}{/\degreeCelsius} \times \SI{11.95}{\degreeCelsius} \approx \SI{478}{\ohm}
\]

The new resistance $R'$ is:
\[
R' = R + \Delta R = \SI{10000}{\ohm} + \SI{478}{\ohm} = \SI{10478}{\ohm}
\]

The new time constant $\tau'$ is:
\[
\tau' = R' \cdot C = \SI{10478}{\ohm} \times \SI{10e-6}{\farad} \approx \SI{0

