\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{amssymb}

\begin{document}

Let $l$ be the length of the coaxial cylindrical capacitor, $a$ the radius of the central wire, and $b$ the radius of the tube. The conductors are connected to a battery of $V$ volts and a current $I$ is passed. Calculate:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] the capacitance per unit length of the cable,
    \item[(b)] the inductance per unit length.
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Capacitance per Unit Length}

The capacitance per unit length $C'$ of a coaxial cable is given by the formula:
\[
C' = \frac{2\pi \varepsilon}{\ln\left(\frac{b}{a}\right)}
\]
where $\varepsilon$ is the permittivity of the medium between the conductors.

\subsection*{(b) Inductance per Unit Length}

The inductance per unit length $L'$ of a coaxial cable is given by the formula:
\[
L' = \frac{\mu}{2\pi} \ln\left(\frac{b}{a}\right)
\]
where $\mu$ is the permeability of the medium between the conductors.

\end{document}

