\section*{Poynting Vector and Time-Averaged Power}

The Poynting vector \(\mathbf{S}\) represents the power per unit area carried by an electromagnetic wave and is given by:

\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{S} = \mathbf{E} \times \mathbf{H}
\end{equation}

where \(\mathbf{E}\) is the electric field and \(\mathbf{H}\) is the magnetic field. In free space, the magnetic field \(\mathbf{H}\) can be expressed in terms of the magnetic field intensity \(\mathbf{B}\) as:

\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{H} = \frac{\mathbf{B}}{\mu_0}
\end{equation}

where \(\mu_0\) is the permeability of free space. For a plane electromagnetic wave, the relationship between \(\mathbf{E}\) and \(\mathbf{B}\) is given by:

\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{B} = \frac{\mathbf{E}}{c}
\end{equation}

where \(c\) is the speed of light in vacuum. Substituting this into the expression for \(\mathbf{H}\), we have:

\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{H} = \frac{\mathbf{E}}{\mu_0 c}
\end{equation}

Thus, the Poynting vector becomes:

\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{S} = \mathbf{E} \times \left(\frac{\mathbf{E}}{\mu_0 c}\right) = \frac{1}{\mu_0 c} (\mathbf{E} \times \mathbf{E})
\end{equation}

Since \(\mathbf{E} \times \mathbf{E} = 0\) for parallel vectors, we consider the time-averaged Poynting vector \(\langle \mathbf{S} \rangle\), which is given by:

\begin{equation}
    \langle \mathbf{S} \rangle = \frac{1}{2} \frac{E_0^2}{\mu_0 c}
\end{equation}

where \(E_0\) is the amplitude of the electric field. Therefore, the time-averaged power per unit area carried by a plane electromagnetic wave in free space is:

\begin{equation}
    \langle S \rangle = \frac{E_0^2}{2 \mu_0 c}
\end{equation}

This completes the derivation of the time-averaged power per unit area for a plane electromagnetic wave in free space.

\end{document}

