\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

An electromagnetic plane wave in vacuum has an electric field given by:
\[
E_z = 10 \sin\left(\pi (2 \times 10^6 x - 6 \times 10^{14} t)\right), \quad E_x = E_y = 0.
\]

Find:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Frequency
    \item Wavelength
    \item Speed
    \item Electric field amplitude
    \item Polarization
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Solution:}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Frequency:} \\
    The angular frequency $\omega$ is given by the term $6 \times 10^{14}$ in the argument of the sine function. Thus, the frequency $f$ is:
    \[
    \omega = 2\pi f = 6 \times 10^{14} \implies f = \frac{6 \times 10^{14}}{2\pi} \approx 9.55 \times 10^{13} \, \text{Hz}
    \]

    \item \textbf{Wavelength:} \\
    The wave number $k$ is given by the term $2 \times 10^6$. The wavelength $\lambda$ is:
    \[
    k = \frac{2\pi}{\lambda} = 2 \times 10^6 \implies \lambda = \frac{2\pi}{2 \times 10^6} \approx 3.14 \times 10^{-6} \, \text{m}
    \]

    \item \textbf{Speed:} \\
    The speed of the wave $v$ is given by the relation $v = \frac{\omega}{k}$:
    \[
    v = \frac{6 \times 10^{14}}{2 \times 10^6} = 3 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s}
    \]

    \item \textbf{Electric field amplitude:} \\
    The amplitude of the electric field is the coefficient of the sine function:
    \[
    E_0 = 10 \, \text{V/m}
    \]

    \item \textbf{Polarization:} \\
    Since $E_x = E_y = 0$ and $E_z \neq 0$, the wave is linearly polarized along the $z$-axis.
\end{enumerate}

\end{document}

