\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

Microwaves of frequency \(\nu = \SI{800}{\mega\hertz}\) are beamed by a stationary policeman towards a receding car speeding at \(\SI{90}{\kilo\meter\per\hour}\). What beat frequency was registered by the radar?

\section*{Solution}

To find the beat frequency, we need to calculate the frequency shift due to the Doppler effect. The formula for the observed frequency \( \nu' \) when the source is stationary and the observer is moving away is given by:

\[
\nu' = \nu \left( 1 - \frac{v}{c} \right)
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \(\nu = \SI{800}{\mega\hertz}\) is the original frequency of the microwaves,
    \item \(v = \SI{90}{\kilo\meter\per\hour} = \frac{90 \times 1000}{3600} = \SI{25}{\meter\per\second}\) is the speed of the car,
    \item \(c = \SI{3e8}{\meter\per\second}\) is the speed of light.
\end{itemize}

Substituting the values into the equation:

\[
\nu' = \SI{800}{\mega\hertz} \left( 1 - \frac{\SI{25}{\meter\per\second}}{\SI{3e8}{\meter\per\second}} \right)
\]

\[
\nu' \approx \SI{800}{\mega\hertz} \left( 1 - 8.33 \times 10^{-8} \right)
\]

\[
\nu' \approx \SI{800}{\mega\hertz} - \SI{0.0667}{\hertz}
\]

The beat frequency \( f_b \) is the difference between the original frequency and the observed frequency:

\[
f_b = \nu - \nu' = \SI{0.0667}{\hertz}
\]

Thus, the beat frequency registered by the radar is approximately \(\SI{0.067}{\hertz}\).

\end{document}

