\usepackage{amssymb}

\begin{document}

\section*{Poynting's Theorem}

Poynting's theorem is a fundamental statement in electromagnetism that relates the flow of electromagnetic energy to the work done on charges and the rate of energy storage in the fields. The theorem can be expressed as:

\begin{equation}
    \nabla \cdot (\mathbf{E} \times \mathbf{H}) + \mathbf{E} \cdot \frac{\partial \mathbf{D}}{\partial t} + \mathbf{H} \cdot \frac{\partial \mathbf{B}}{\partial t} + \mathbf{E} \cdot \mathbf{j} = 0
\end{equation}

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\mathbf{E}$ is the electric field,
    \item $\mathbf{H}$ is the magnetic field intensity,
    \item $\mathbf{D}$ is the electric displacement field,
    \item $\mathbf{B}$ is the magnetic flux density,
    \item $\mathbf{j}$ is the current density.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Interpretation}

The equation can be interpreted as follows:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\nabla \cdot (\mathbf{E} \times \mathbf{H})$ represents the divergence of the Poynting vector, which describes the flow of electromagnetic energy per unit area per unit time.
    \item $\mathbf{E} \cdot \frac{\partial \mathbf{D}}{\partial t}$ and $\mathbf{H} \cdot \frac{\partial \mathbf{B}}{\partial t}$ represent the rate of change of energy stored in the electric and magnetic fields, respectively.
    \item $\mathbf{E} \cdot \mathbf{j}$ represents the work done on charges per unit volume, which is the power density supplied to the charges.
\end{itemize}

The theorem essentially states that the rate of energy leaving a given volume (through the surface) plus the rate of increase of energy stored in the fields within the volume is equal to the work done on the charges within that volume.

\end{document}

