\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{amssymb}

\begin{document}

From Maxwell's equations, one can derive a wave equation for a dielectric of the form:
\begin{equation}
    \nabla^2 \mathbf{E} - \mu_0 \varepsilon_0 \varepsilon_r \frac{\partial^2 \mathbf{E}}{\partial t^2} - \mu_0 \sigma_N \frac{\partial \mathbf{E}}{\partial t} = 0
\end{equation}
where $\mathbf{E}$ is the electric field, $t$ is the time, $\varepsilon_r$ is the relative permittivity, and $\sigma_N$ is the electrical conductivity.

To derive a dispersion relation, we substitute a traveling wave solution of the form:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{E}(\mathbf{r}, t) = \mathbf{E}_0 e^{i(\mathbf{k} \cdot \mathbf{r} - \omega t)}
\end{equation}
into the wave equation. Here, $\mathbf{k}$ is the wave vector and $\omega$ is the angular frequency.

Substituting this solution into the wave equation, we have:
\begin{align*}
    \nabla^2 \mathbf{E} & = -k^2 \mathbf{E}, \\
    \frac{\partial^2 \mathbf{E}}{\partial t^2} & = -\omega^2 \mathbf{E}, \\
    \frac{\partial \mathbf{E}}{\partial t} & = -i\omega \mathbf{E}.
\end{align*}

Plugging these into the wave equation gives:
\begin{equation}
    -k^2 \mathbf{E} - \mu_0 \varepsilon_0 \varepsilon_r (-\omega^2 \mathbf{E}) - \mu_0 \sigma_N (-i\omega \mathbf{E}) = 0
\end{equation}

Simplifying, we obtain the dispersion relation:
\begin{equation}
    k^2 = \mu_0 \varepsilon_0 \varepsilon_r \omega^2 + i \mu_0 \sigma_N \omega
\end{equation}

This is the desired dispersion relation for the wave equation in a dielectric medium.

\end{document}

