\section*{Problem Statement}

An electromagnetic wave is normally incident on a dielectric discontinuity. Use appropriate boundary conditions to calculate the reflectance $R$ and the transmittance $T$, and show that $T + R = 1$.

\section*{Solution}

When a plane wave is normally incident on a boundary between two dielectric media, the boundary conditions at the interface require the continuity of the tangential components of the electric and magnetic fields. For normal incidence, these conditions reduce to the continuity of the electric field $E$ and the magnetic field $H$ across the boundary.

Let the incident wave be described by the electric field $E_i = E_0 e^{i(k_1 z - \omega t)}$, where $k_1$ is the wave number in the first medium. The reflected wave is $E_r = R E_0 e^{i(-k_1 z - \omega t)}$, and the transmitted wave is $E_t = T E_0 e^{i(k_2 z - \omega t)}$, where $k_2$ is the wave number in the second medium.

The boundary conditions at $z = 0$ are:
\begin{align}
    E_i + E_r &= E_t, \\
    \frac{1}{\mu_1} (E_i - E_r) &= \frac{1}{\mu_2} E_t,
\end{align}
where $\mu_1$ and $\mu_2$ are the permeabilities of the first and second media, respectively.

Solving these equations for $R$ and $T$, we find:
\begin{align}
    R &= \frac{\mu_2 k_1 - \mu_1 k_2}{\mu_2 k_1 + \mu_1 k_2}, \\
    T &= \frac{2 \mu_2 k_1}{\mu_2 k_1 + \mu_1 k_2}.
\end{align}

To show that $T + R = 1$, we compute:
\begin{align*}
    T + R &= \frac{2 \mu_2 k_1}{\mu_2 k_1 + \mu_1 k_2} + \frac{\mu_2 k_1 - \mu_1 k_2}{\mu_2 k_1 + \mu_1 k_2} \\
    &= \frac{2 \mu_2 k_1 + \mu_2 k_1 - \mu_1 k_2}{\mu_2 k_1 + \mu_1 k_2} \\
    &= \frac{(\mu_2 k_1 + \mu_1 k_2) + (\mu_2 k_1 - \mu_1 k_2)}{\mu_2 k_1 + \mu_1 k_2} \\
    &= \frac{2 \mu_2 k_1}{\mu_2 k_1 + \mu_1 k_2} \\
    &= 1.
\end{align*}

Thus, $T + R = 1$, as required.

\end{document}

