\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

An uncharged dielectric cube of material with relative permittivity $\varepsilon_r = 6$ contains a uniform electric field $\mathbf{E}$ of \SI{2}{\kilo\volt\per\meter}, which is perpendicular to one of the faces. What is the surface charge density induced on this face? [University of Manchester 2006]

\section*{Solution}

The surface charge density $\sigma$ induced on the face of the dielectric can be determined using the relation between the electric displacement field $\mathbf{D}$ and the electric field $\mathbf{E}$ in a dielectric material:

\[
\mathbf{D} = \varepsilon_0 \varepsilon_r \mathbf{E}
\]

where $\varepsilon_0$ is the permittivity of free space, approximately \SI{8.85e-12}{\farad\per\meter}.

The surface charge density $\sigma$ is given by the normal component of the electric displacement field:

\[
\sigma = \mathbf{D} \cdot \hat{n}
\]

Since the electric field is perpendicular to the face, the normal component is simply:

\[
\sigma = \varepsilon_0 \varepsilon_r E
\]

Substituting the given values:

\[
\sigma = (\SI{8.85e-12}{\farad\per\meter}) \times 6 \times \SI{2e3}{\volt\per\meter}
\]

Calculating this gives:

\[
\sigma = \SI{1.062e-7}{\coulomb\per\meter\squared}
\]

Thus, the surface charge density induced on the face is approximately \SI{1.062e-7}{\coulomb\per\meter\squared}.

\end{document}

