\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

Given the dispersion relation \(\omega = a k^2\), calculate:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The phase velocity.
    \item The group velocity.
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Phase Velocity}

The phase velocity \(v_p\) is defined as the ratio of the angular frequency \(\omega\) to the wave number \(k\):
\[
v_p = \frac{\omega}{k}
\]
Substituting the given dispersion relation \(\omega = a k^2\) into the equation for phase velocity, we get:
\[
v_p = \frac{a k^2}{k} = a k
\]

\subsection*{(b) Group Velocity}

The group velocity \(v_g\) is defined as the derivative of the angular frequency \(\omega\) with respect to the wave number \(k\):
\[
v_g = \frac{d\omega}{dk}
\]
Differentiating the given dispersion relation \(\omega = a k^2\) with respect to \(k\), we find:
\[
v_g = \frac{d}{dk}(a k^2) = 2a k
\]

Thus, the phase velocity is \(v_p = a k\) and the group velocity is \(v_g = 2a k\).

\end{document}

