\begin{document}

\title{Waveguide Problem}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

For a rectangular waveguide of width \SI{2.5}{\centi\meter}, determine the free-space wavelength of radiation required for energy to traverse \SI{50}{\meter} of the guide in \SI{1}{\micro\second}. Additionally, calculate the phase velocity under these conditions.

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{Given Data}

\begin{itemize}
    \item Width of the waveguide, \( a = \SI{2.5}{\centi\meter} = \SI{0.025}{\meter} \)
    \item Length of the waveguide, \( L = \SI{50}{\meter} \)
    \item Time for energy to traverse the guide, \( t = \SI{1}{\micro\second} = \SI{1e-6}{\second} \)
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Calculation of Free-Space Wavelength}

The speed of light in free space is \( c = \SI{3e8}{\meter\per\second} \).

The group velocity \( v_g \) in the waveguide is given by:
\[
v_g = \frac{L}{t} = \frac{\SI{50}{\meter}}{\SI{1e-6}{\second}} = \SI{5e7}{\meter\per\second}
\]

The cutoff wavelength \( \lambda_c \) for the \(\text{TE}_{10}\) mode in a rectangular waveguide is:
\[
\lambda_c = 2a = 2 \times \SI{0.025}{\meter} = \SI{0.05}{\meter}
\]

The free-space wavelength \( \lambda_0 \) is related to the group velocity and cutoff wavelength by:
\[
v_g = c \sqrt{1 - \left(\frac{\lambda_0}{\lambda_c}\right)^2}
\]

Solving for \( \lambda_0 \):
\[
\left(\frac{\lambda_0}{\lambda_c}\right)^2 = 1 - \left(\frac{v_g}{c}\right)^2
\]
\[
\lambda_0 = \lambda_c \sqrt{1 - \left(\frac{v_g}{c}\right)^2}
\]

Substitute the known values:
\[
\lambda_0 = \SI{0.05}{\meter} \sqrt{1 - \left(\frac{\SI{5e7}{\meter\per\second}}{\SI{3e8}{\meter\per\second}}\right)^2}
\]

\subsection*{Calculation of Phase Velocity}

The phase velocity \( v_p \) in the waveguide is given by:
\[
v_p = \frac{c}{\sqrt{1 - \left(\frac{\lambda_0}{\lambda_c}\right)^2}}
\]

Substitute the expression for \( \lambda_0 \):
\[
v_p = \frac{c}{\sqrt{1 - \left(\frac{v_g}{c}\right)^2}}
\]

\end{document}

