\section*{Problem}

For a rectangular waveguide of width \( a = \SI{2.5}{\centi\meter} \), calculate the following for the dominant mode (\( \text{TE}_{10} \)) given a free-space wavelength of \( \lambda_0 = \SI{4}{\centi\meter} \):

\begin{enumerate}
    \item The phase velocity \( v_p \).
    \item The group velocity \( v_g \).
    \item The guide wavelength \( \lambda_g \).
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Phase Velocity}

The phase velocity \( v_p \) in a waveguide is given by:

\[
v_p = \frac{c}{\sqrt{1 - \left(\frac{\lambda_0}{2a}\right)^2}}
\]

where \( c = \SI{3e8}{\meter\per\second} \) is the speed of light in vacuum.

Substituting the given values:

\[
