\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] Calculate the guide wavelength for a rectangular waveguide of width \( a = 5 \, \text{cm} \) if the free-space wavelength is \( \lambda_0 = 8 \, \text{cm} \).
    \item[(b)] What is the cut-off wavelength for the guide?
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Guide Wavelength}

The guide wavelength \( \lambda_g \) in a rectangular waveguide is given by the formula:

\[
\lambda_g = \frac{\lambda_0}{\sqrt{1 - \left(\frac{\lambda_0}{2a}\right)^2}}
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( \lambda_0 = 8 \, \text{cm} \) is the free-space wavelength,
    \item \( a = 5 \, \text{cm} \) is the width of the waveguide.
\end{itemize}

Substituting the given values:

\[
\lambda_g = \frac{8}{\sqrt{1 - \left(\frac{8}{2 \times 5}\right)^2}} = \frac{8}{\sqrt{1 - \left(\frac{8}{10}\right)^2}} = \frac{8}{\sqrt{1 - 0.64}}
\]

\[
\lambda_g = \frac{8}{\sqrt{0.36}} = \frac{8}{0.6} = 13.33 \, \text{cm}
\]

\subsection*{(b) Cut-off Wavelength}

The cut-off wavelength \( \lambda_c \) for the dominant mode in a rectangular waveguide is given by:

\[
\lambda_c = 2a
\]

Substituting the given width:

\[
\lambda_c = 2 \times 5 = 10 \, \text{cm}
\]

\end{document}

