\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Explanation of Mirage Using Optical Path}

A mirage is an optical phenomenon that occurs due to the refraction of light in layers of air with varying temperatures. This can be explained using the concept of optical path, which is the path that light takes as it travels through a medium.

Early in the morning, on a sunny day, the heat of the sun warms the surface of a long straight road. This creates a thin layer of warm air above the road surface, with cooler air above it. The refractive index of air decreases with increasing temperature, meaning that light travels faster in warmer air than in cooler air.

Consider a possible light ray path as illustrated in Fig. \ref{fig:mirage}. As light travels from the cooler air into the warmer air near the road surface, it bends away from the normal due to the decrease in refractive index. This bending of light, or refraction, causes the light rays to curve upwards. 

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{mirage_example.png}
    \caption{Illustration of light ray path in a mirage.}
    \label{fig:mirage}
\end{figure}

The observer perceives these bent light rays as coming from the ground, creating the illusion of a pool of water or a reflective surface. This is because the brain interprets light as traveling in straight lines, leading to the perception of an inverted image of the sky on the road.

Thus, the optical path of light, altered by the varying refractive indices of the air layers, results in the fascinating phenomenon of a mirage.

\end{document}

