\begin{document}

\title{Astronomical Telescope Problem}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

An astronomical telescope has the focal lengths of the objective and eyepiece in the ratio 8:1. Both lenses are convex. A tower 100 m tall is at a distance of 10,000 m. Determine:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] The location of the image.
    \item[(b)] The height of the image.
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

Given:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Focal length ratio: \( f_o : f_e = 8:1 \)
    \item Height of the tower: \( h = 100 \, \text{m} \)
    \item Distance to the tower: \( u = 10,000 \, \text{m} \)
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{(a) Location of the Image}

The focal length of the objective lens \( f_o \) is much larger than that of the eyepiece \( f_e \). Assume:
\[
f_o = 8f_e
\]

Using the lens formula for the objective lens:
\[
\frac{1}{v} - \frac{1}{u} = \frac{1}{f_o}
\]

Substituting the given values:
\[
\frac{1}{v} - \frac{1}{10,000} = \frac{1}{8f_e}
\]

Since the object distance \( u \) is very large compared to the focal length, we can approximate:
\[
v \approx f_o = 8f_e
\]

Thus, the image formed by the objective lens is at its focal point, \( v = 8f_e \).

\subsection*{(b) Height of the Image}

The magnification \( M \) produced by the objective lens is given by:
\[
M = \frac{v}{u} = \frac{8f_e}{10,000}
\]

The height of the image \( h' \) is given by:
\[
h' = M \times h = \left(\frac{8f_e}{10,000}\right) \times 100
\]

Simplifying:
\[
h' = \frac{800f_e}{10,000} = \frac{8f_e}{100} = 0.08f_e
\]

Thus, the height of the image is \( 0.08f_e \).

\end{document}

