\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem A1}

A \SI{0}{\watt} laser beam is concentrated by a lens of a cross-sectional area of \SI{10^{-5}}{\centi\meter\squared}. Find the corresponding (a) intensity and (b) the amplitude of the electric field.

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Intensity}

The intensity \( I \) of a laser beam is given by the formula:
\[
I = \frac{P}{A}
\]
where \( P \) is the power of the laser and \( A \) is the cross-sectional area.

Given:
\[
P = \SI{0}{\watt}, \quad A = \SI{10^{-5}}{\centi\meter\squared} = \SI{10^{-9}}{\meter\squared}
\]

Substituting the values, we get:
\[
I = \frac{\SI{0}{\watt}}{\SI{10^{-9}}{\meter\squared}} = \SI{0}{\watt\per\meter\squared}
\]

\subsection*{(b) Amplitude of the Electric Field}

The intensity \( I \) is also related to the amplitude of the electric field \( E_0 \) by the equation:
\[
I = \frac{1}{2} c \varepsilon_0 E_0^2
\]
where \( c \) is the speed of light in vacuum and \( \varepsilon_0 \) is the permittivity of free space.

Rearranging for \( E_0 \), we have:
\[
E_0 = \sqrt{\frac{2I}{c \varepsilon_0}}
\]

Substituting \( I = \SI{0}{\watt\per\meter\squared} \), we find:
\[
E_0 = \sqrt{\frac{2 \times \SI{0}{\watt\per\meter\squared}}{c \varepsilon_0}} = \SI{0}{\volt\per\meter}
\]

Thus, the amplitude of the electric field is \SI{0}{\volt\per\meter}.

\end{document}

