\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

Consider two point sources $s_1$ and $s_2$, as shown in Fig. 15.10, which emit coherent waves. Show that curves such as that traced by point $p$, for which the phase difference for rays $r_1$ and $r_2$ is a constant, are hyperboloids in three dimensions.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{figure15_10.png} % Replace with actual figure file
    \caption{Diagram illustrating point sources $s_1$ and $s_2$ emitting coherent waves.}
    \label{fig:15_10}
\end{figure}

To demonstrate this, consider the phase difference $\Delta \phi$ between the rays $r_1$ and $r_2$ reaching point $p$. The phase difference is given by:

\begin{equation}
    \Delta \phi = k (d_1 - d_2) = \text{constant},
\end{equation}

where $k$ is the wave number, and $d_1$ and $d_2$ are the distances from the point sources $s_1$ and $s_2$ to the point $p$, respectively. This condition implies that the difference in path lengths $d_1 - d_2$ is constant.

The locus of points for which the difference in distances from two fixed points (the foci) is constant is a hyperboloid. Therefore, the surface traced by point $p$ in three dimensions, where the phase difference is constant, forms a hyperboloid.

\end{document}

