\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Fresnel's Biprism Experiment}

In a Fresnel's biprism experiment, the bandwidth of 0.195 mm is observed at a distance of 1 m from the slit. The image of the coherent sources is then produced at the same distance from the slit by placing a convex lens 30 cm from the slit. Two images are found to be separated by 0.7 cm. Calculate the wavelength of light used. [Kakatiya University 2002]

\subsection*{Solution}

Given:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Bandwidth, $B = 0.195 \, \text{mm} = 0.195 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{m}$
    \item Distance from the slit to the screen, $D = 1 \, \text{m}$
    \item Distance between the images, $d = 0.7 \, \text{cm} = 0.7 \times 10^{-2} \, \text{m}$
    \item Distance of the lens from the slit, $d_1 = 30 \, \text{cm} = 0.3 \, \text{m}$
\end{itemize}

The formula for the bandwidth in a biprism experiment is given by:
\[
B = \frac{\lambda D}{d}
\]

Rearranging for the wavelength $\lambda$, we have:
\[
\lambda = \frac{B \cdot d}{D}
\]

Substituting the known values:
\[
\lambda = \frac{0.195 \times 10^{-3} \times 0.7 \times 10^{-2}}{1}
\]

Calculating the wavelength:
\[
\lambda = \frac{0.195 \times 0.7 \times 10^{-5}}{1} = 0.1365 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{m}
\]

Thus, the wavelength of light used is:
\[
\lambda = 1.365 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m} = 136.5 \, \text{nm}
\]

\end{document}

