\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}
\usepackage{xcolor}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A thin film of thickness $t = 4 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{cm}$ and refractive index $n = 1.5$ is illuminated by white light normal to its surface. Which color will be intensified in the visible spectrum?

\section*{Solution}

For constructive interference in a thin film, the condition is given by:

\begin{equation}
2nt = m\lambda,
\end{equation}

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $n = 1.5$ is the refractive index of the film,
    \item $t = 4 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{cm} = 4 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m}$ is the thickness of the film,
    \item $\lambda$ is the wavelength of light in vacuum,
    \item $m$ is an integer (order of interference).
\end{itemize}

Rearranging for $\lambda$, we have:

\begin{equation}
\lambda = \frac{2nt}{m}.
\end{equation}

Substituting the known values:

\begin{equation}
\lambda = \frac{2 \times 1.5 \times 4 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m}}{m} = \frac{1.2 \times 10^{-6} \, \text{m}}{m}.
\end{equation}

To find the wavelength in the visible spectrum (approximately \SIrange{400}{700}{\nano\meter}), we need to choose an appropriate $m$:

\begin{itemize}
    \item For $m = 2$: 
    \begin{equation}
    \lambda = \frac{1.2 \times 10^{-6} \, \text{m}}{2} = 600 \, \text{nm}.
    \end{equation}
\end{itemize}

Thus, the color intensified in the visible spectrum is approximately \textcolor{orange}{orange} or \textcolor{yellow}{yellow}, corresponding to a wavelength of \SI{600}{\nano\meter}.

\end{document}

