\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\title{Wavelength Calculation using Michelson's Interferometer}
\author{Delhi University Physics Problem}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

In Michelsons interferometer, 100 fringes cross the field of view when the movable mirror is displaced through \SI{0.02948}{\milli\meter}. Calculate the wavelength of the monochromatic light used.

\section*{Solution}

The number of fringes \( N \) that cross the field of view is related to the displacement \( d \) of the mirror and the wavelength \( \lambda \) of the light by the formula:

\[
N = \frac{2d}{\lambda}
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( N = 100 \) is the number of fringes,
    \item \( d = \SI{0.02948}{\milli\meter} = \SI{0.02948e-3}{\meter} \) is the displacement of the mirror,
    \item \( \lambda \) is the wavelength of the light.
\end{itemize}

Rearranging the formula to solve for \( \lambda \), we have:

\[
\lambda = \frac{2d}{N}
\]

Substituting the given values:

\[
\lambda = \frac{2 \times \SI{0.02948e-3}{\meter}}{100}
\]

Calculating the wavelength:

\[
\lambda = \frac{\SI{0.05896e-3}{\meter}}{100} = \SI{5.896e-7}{\meter}
\]

Thus, the wavelength of the monochromatic light used is \(\lambda = \SI{589.6}{\nano\meter}\).

\end{document}

