\begin{document}

\title{Resolving Power of a Fabry-Prot Interferometer}
\author{University of Wales, Aberystwyth 2005}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem}

The plates of a Fabry-Prot interferometer have a reflectance amplitude of \( r = 0.90 \). Calculate the resolving power of wavelengths near 600 nm when the plates are separated by 2 mm.

\section*{Solution}

The resolving power \( R \) of a Fabry-Prot interferometer is given by the formula:

\[
R = \frac{\lambda}{\Delta \lambda} = \frac{2 \pi n d}{\lambda (1 - r^2)}
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( \lambda = 600 \, \text{nm} = 600 \times 10^{-9} \, \text{m} \) is the wavelength of light,
    \item \( r = 0.90 \) is the reflectance amplitude,
    \item \( d = 2 \, \text{mm} = 2 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{m} \) is the separation between the plates,
    \item \( n \) is the refractive index of the medium between the plates (assuming air, \( n \approx 1 \)).
\end{itemize}

Substituting the given values into the formula, we have:

\[
R = \frac{2 \pi \times 1 \times 2 \times 10^{-3}}{600 \times 10^{-9} \times (1 - 0.90^2)}
\]

Calculating the denominator:

\[
1 - r^2 = 1 - (0.90)^2 = 1 - 0.81 = 0.19
\]

Thus, the resolving power is:

\[
R = \frac{2 \pi \times 2 \times 10^{-3}}{600 \times 10^{-9} \times 0.19}
\]

\[
R \approx \frac{12.5664 \times 10^{-3}}{114 \times 10^{-9}}
\]

\[
R \approx 1.10 \times 10^5
\]

Therefore, the resolving power of the Fabry-Prot interferometer for wavelengths near 600 nm is approximately \( 1.10 \times 10^5 \).

\end{document}

