\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A grating of width 3$''$ is ruled with 10,000 lines/in. Find the smallest wavelength separation that can be resolved in the first-order spectrum at a mean wavelength of 6000 . [Kakatiya University 2002]

\section*{Solution}

To solve this problem, we use the Rayleigh criterion for resolving power, which is given by:

\[
R = \frac{\lambda}{\Delta \lambda} = mN
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( R \) is the resolving power,
    \item \( \lambda \) is the mean wavelength,
    \item \( \Delta \lambda \) is the smallest wavelength difference that can be resolved,
    \item \( m \) is the order of the spectrum (in this case, \( m = 1 \) for first-order),
    \item \( N \) is the total number of lines on the grating.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Given:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Grating width = 3 inches,
    \item Lines per inch = 10,000,
    \item Mean wavelength \( \lambda = 6000 \) .
\end{itemize}

First, calculate \( N \), the total number of lines on the grating:

\[
N = (\text{lines per inch}) \times (\text{width in inches}) = 10,000 \times 3 = 30,000
\]

Now, use the resolving power formula to find \( \Delta \lambda \):

\[
R = mN = 1 \times 30,000 = 30,000
\]

\[
\frac{\lambda}{\Delta \lambda} = 30,000 \implies \Delta \lambda = \frac{\lambda}{30,000}
\]

Substitute the given mean wavelength:

\[
\Delta \lambda = \frac{6000 \, \text{}}{30,000} = 0.2 \, \text{}
\]

Thus, the smallest wavelength separation that can be resolved in the first-order spectrum is:

\[
\boxed{0.2 \, \text{}}
\]

\end{document}

