\section*{Resolution of Two Points on the Moon}

To find the separation of two points on the moon that can be resolved by a 500 cm telescope, we use the Rayleigh criterion for angular resolution:

\[
\theta = 1.22 \frac{\lambda}{D}
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \(\theta\) is the angular resolution in radians,
    \item \(\lambda\) is the wavelength of light,
    \item \(D\) is the diameter of the telescope.
\end{itemize}

Given:
\begin{align*}
    \lambda &= 5500 \, \text{\AA} = 5500 \times 10^{-10} \, \text{m}, \\
    D &= 500 \, \text{cm} = 5 \, \text{m}, \\
    L &= 3.8 \times 10^5 \, \text{km} = 3.8 \times 10^8 \, \text{m}.
\end{align*}

First, calculate the angular resolution \(\theta\):

\[
\theta = 1.22 \frac{5500 \times 10^{-10}}{5} = 1.22 \times 1100 \times 10^{-10} = 1.342 \times 10^{-6} \, \text{radians}
\]

The linear separation \(s\) on the moon that can be resolved is given by:

\[
s = L \cdot \theta
\]

Substituting the values:

\[
s = 3.8 \times 10^8 \times 1.342 \times 10^{-6} \approx 509.96 \, \text{m}
\]

Therefore, the separation of two points on the moon that can be resolved by the telescope is approximately \(510 \, \text{m}\).

\end{document}

